<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab League Chief Views Civil War in Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arab League Chief Views Civil War in Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3005110794 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 30 May 94 p 132 </F>
<F P=103> AU3005110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Arab League Secretary General Ismat </F>
'Abd-al-Majid by unidentified correspondent; place and date not 
given: "We Are Supposed To Mediate"] 
  [Text] [DER SPIEGEL] Why has the Arab League failed in 
the conflict in Yemen? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] We have not failed; we made enormous efforts 
to defuse the conflict. 
  [DER SPIEGEL] But this has not prevented the fratricidal 
war. 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] The Arab League does not have the right to 
intervene in the internal conflicts of a member state. The 
Republic of Yemen officially still exists as a unified state. 
Nevertheless, the Arab League remains an important political 
instrument, and that includes in the conflict in Yemen as well. 
  [DER SPIEGEL] What can you do? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] Both parties to the war in Yemen now want to 
negotiate. The Arab League has been called upon to mediate 
between Sana and Aden. 
  [DER SPIEGEL] Are you thinking of sending peacekeeping 
forces under the green banner of the Arab League? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] If both sides consider this appropriate, why 
not? 
  [DER SPIEGEL] In other conflicts in the region, the League 
has also been ineffective -- for instance, in Somalia. 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] No state whatsoever existed there, which 
made the costly intervention of UN troops difficult. 
International organizations cannot replace a state. 
  [DER SPIEGEL] The Arab League also stayed out of the 
rapprochement between the Israelis and the Palestinians. 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] Not at all. By unanimously recognizing the 
respective UN resolutions, we have clearly accelerated the peace 
process. 
  [DER SPIEGEL] Are all Arab League members really ready to 
recognize Israel's right to exist? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] All, without any exception -- under the 
precondition that all parties strive for a just peace on the 
basis of "land for peace." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

