<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentary Leader Denounces South Yemen Secession </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliamentary Leader Denounces South Yemen Secession </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3105123494 Paris AFP in English 1019 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3105123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tripoli, May 31 (AFP) -- Libya rejects the secession 
by southern Yemen and will oppose any plans to send UN troops to 
keep the warring sides apart, a parliamentary leader said here 
Tuesday [31 May]. 
  "There exists only one state in Yemen, the republic of Yemen 
(which merged north and south in 1990) and nobody has the right 
to interfere in its internal affairs," parliament's foreign 
affairs secretary, Sa'd Mujbir, told AFP. 
  "Libya supports Yemen's unity and is opposed to any 
secession," he said. 
  Southern leader 'Ali Salim al-Bid proclaimed an independent 
state with Aden as its capital on May 21, two weeks after civil 
war broke out. His northern rival, President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih, has vowed to crush the "rebellion." 
  Libyan officials had earlier stopped short of denouncing the 
secession, issuing statements of support for Yemen's unity. 
  Mujbir also warned against any "plan to send troops" from 
the 
United Nations to keep the warring sides apart, adding that will 
"repeat the catastrophes which took place in ex-Yugoslavia and 
Somalia." 
  The Security Council is due to debate the Yemeni conflict on 
Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

