<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Chief on Possible Russian Weapons Purchase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Chief on Possible Russian Weapons Purchase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205084794 Tallinn BNS in English 1235 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Apr 30, BNS -- It is absolutely possible 
that Estonia would buy anti-tank and anti-aircraft weapons from 
Russia, the commander in chief of the Estonian defense forces 
said. 
  Maj. Gen. Aleksander Einseln in remarks to reporters about 
his last week's visit to Moscow and talks with Russian army 
leadership said that Estonia wants to buy high-quality weapons 
at a low price. "If it is possible for us to get them from 
Russia, we'll buy weapons from there," he said. 
  Einseln quoted the chief of Russia's General Staff, Col. 
Gen. 
Mikhail Kolesnikov as reconfirming that Russia will pull its 
troops from Estonia. "But we didn't talks about dates at the 
meeting," he said. 
  The Estonian commander in chief, who visited Moscow on Apr. 
20- 22, also proposed to the Russian Defense Ministry to set up 
a joint work group that would be able to quickly resolve all 
problems that may emerge in connection with the withdrawal from 
Estonia. Kolesnikov had said the proposal would be taken for 
consideration. 
  Also discussed at the meetings were prospects for military 
cooperation between Estonia and Russia after the Russian troops 
will have left Estonia. 
  "We don't think that our contacts with the Russian military 
will end after the troop withdrawal. We must also look into the 
future and make clear the possible directions of working 
closely," Einseln said. 
  The Estonian commander in chief has earlier said that the 
country could start sending its cadets to be trained for 
officers at Russian military colleges. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

