<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Brazausksas Receives Message From Yeltsin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Brazausksas Receives Message From Yeltsin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904172394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1543 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas received 
Russian Ambassador Nikolay Obertyshev who handed him a message 
from Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  Following the meeting, Brazauskas told journalists that he 
had received a response from Yeltsin to his letter of early 
April saying that some of the Lithuanian-Russian agreements 
signed by the two men in November 1993 had not been observed. 
  Brazauskas said that Yeltsin's letter called for activating 
bilateral talks. He thought that both countries wanted that. 
  He added that even before the letter was received the 
Lithuanian leaders had discussed steps to be taken in the near 
future. In particular, it was desirable that a Russian team 
come to Lithuania to discuss Russian transit across that 
country, visa matters and other urgent matters that had not been 
covered by agreements between the two governments. 
  Brazauskas said that Virgilijus Bulovas, head of the 
Lithuanian working group handling talks with CIS member states, 
would complete shortly the study of a Russian draft agreement on 
transit. 
  Dainius Trinkunas, Lithuanian president's foreign policy 
adviser, told Interfax that Yeltsin expressed his gratitude for 
an invitation to visit Lithuania. The date of his visit will be 
agreed on later. 

</TEXT>

