<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vilnius Announces Cutback in Russian Radio, TV </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vilnius Announces Cutback in Russian Radio, TV </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904194794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1802 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Director of the technical center of Lithuanian radio 
and television, Yuosas Niverauskas, has reported that from May 2 
there will be a considerable reduction in the broadcasting of 
the Russian Ostankino television channel in Lithuania. 
  He said that this was a result of the fact that Ostankino 
owed a million litai (approx. 250,000 dollars). Programs will 
only be broadcast from 18:00 local time (19:00 Moscow time). 
  As the debt question remains unresolved it is unclear how 
much longer even evening broadcasting will continue. 
  The remaining time -- from 1:00 to 18:00 -- may well be 
leased to the Litpolinter private studio. 
  As of next week, Niverauskas said, broadcast of the Mayak 
radio station will be suspended, also because of debt. It is 
suggested that relay stations now broadcasting Mayak lease their 
time to private radio companies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60780 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_v_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Hands Down Sentence in Soviet Activists' Trial </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Hands Down Sentence in Soviet Activists' Trial </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2904195294 Tallinn BNS in English 1846 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2904195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Apr 29, BNS -- The Lithuanian Supreme 
Court on Friday [29 April] sentenced eight former Soviet 
activists to varying jail terms for participation in a failed 
coup attempt in January 1991. 
  The trial started last December. The eight were first 
charged with anti-state activities but the accusations were 
changed to milder ones as the trial proceeded. 
  The court sentenced Valeri Ivanov, former leader of the pro- 
Soviet Yedinstvo (Unity) movement, to 3 1/2 years in jail. The 
court said Ivanov helped Soviet troops to guard the Lithuanian 
radio and TV building that was seized Jan. 13, 1991. On that 
day, 13 civilians were killed and hundreds more injured 
defending the TV tower and state institutions from Soviet tanks. 
  The court failed to come up with evidence proving that the 
defendants organized assaults on radio and TV buildings. 
  Ivanov will have to spend only 5 months in jail because the 
time since his arrest was included in the punishment and the 
amnesty law was applied. Some of his accomplices, who were 
sentenced to 3 1/2 years in jail, will be imprisoned for less 
than a month. 
  Two out of eight former activists were fined 1,500 lits and 
one was sentenced to 5 1/2 years in jail. 
  Aleksandr Smotkin, who set off two grenades near a 
Lithuanian 
border post in November 1991, was sentenced to an eight-year 
jail term. The state prosecutor said the explosions endangered 
the lives of four Lithuanian officials, who escaped death only 
by mere chance. The amnesty law was not applied in Smotkin's 
case, but the time since his arrest was included in the 
punishment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60781 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_v_94006" </HT>


