<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Changes in Mapping of Ossetia, Ingushetia Emergency Zone </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Changes in Mapping of Ossetia, Ingushetia Emergency Zone </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2904111094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 29 Apr 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2904111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Natalya Pachegina report under the "Northern Caucasus" </F>
rubric: "Federation Council Confirms President's Edict. Nazran 
and Vladikavkaz Dissatisfied"] 
  [Text] The closed session of the Federation Council of the 
Russian Federation, whose work schedule included the question of 
confirming the Russian president's edict on extending the state 
of emergency in the zone of the Ossetia-Ingushetia conflict, was 
preceded by a meeting of Federation Council Chairman Vladimir 
Shumeyko and the presidents of Ossetia and Ingushetia with Yuriy 
Baturin, the Russian president's national security aide. The 
fourth man, as is rumored, was Sergey Filatov, the president's 
chief of staff. The interlocutors, as an informed source has 
confirmed, agreed that the amendments to the well-known edict of 
4 April made by the Russian Federation president should be 
confirmed by the Federation Council. The edict excluded the 
Republic of North Ossetia's Prigorodnyy Rayon population centers 
of Oktyabrskoye, Kambileyevskoye, Sunzha, and Sputnik, which 
geographically divide the state of emergency zone into two 
parts, from the list of villages whose territories were affected 
by the state of emergency rule. The "amendment" to President 
Yeltsin's edict that followed in the wake of the Ingush citizens 
convoy attacked in Vladikavkaz on 12 April introduced a measure 
of logic in the operation of the state of emergency rule on the 
territory of Prigorodnyy Rayon: all four villages have been 
again "returned" to the state of emergency zone. This 
Federation Council decision brought no satisfaction to the 
presidents of North Ossetia and Ingushetia. In the opinion of 
Akhsarbek Galazov, the edict extending the state of emergency 
rule brings about no serious change in the situation in the 
conflict zone. He is echoed by Yuriy Biragov, North Ossetia's 
Supreme Soviet chairman, who also thinks the Federation Council 
should have taken into consideration the proposal of the 
Provisional Administration, headed by Vladimir Lozovoy, that the 
State of Emergency zone be extended by including in it the 
Ingush territories. The Ingush villages of Galashki, Muzhichi, 
and Ali-Yurt, contiguous on North Ossetia's Prigorodnyy Rayon, 
would have created, Biragov thinks, a real security zone on the 
borders of the two republics. Vladikavkaz representatives also 
disagree with the opinion prevailing in Moscow and in the 
Provisional Administration that the republican law and order 
organs are unable to be on top of the situation on the territory 
entrusted to them. Owing to this, Vladikavkaz cannot recognize 
the primacy of the Provisional Administration's powers in the 
State of Emergency zone over those of the regional 
administration organs. 
  Neither is Ingushetia President Ruslan Aushev quite 
satisfied 
with the extension of the State of Emergency zone. His final 
objective -- the introduction of federal rule in the State of 
Emergency zone -- remains, as before, unrealized. Ingushetia's 
Nazran and Malgobek rayons, which are part of the State of 
Emergency zone, have been once again thus wrongly included, 
Aushev thinks, because their population poses no threat to 
neighboring Ossetia. The Federation Council's confirmation of 
the edict on the conflict zone, in the opinion of the president 
from Nazran, merely corrects the mistake made in the 4 April 
edict. 
  In the meantime, on 27 April Russian Government head Viktor 
Chernomyrdin signed a Russian Government decree expanding the 
powers of Provisional Administration head Vladimir Lozovoy on 
the territory of Mozdok, Prigorodnyy (Republic of North 
Ossetia), Malgobek, and Nazran rayons (Republic of Ingushetia). 
Under the decree, orders and directives of the Provisional 
Administration head are mandatory for federal organs of power of 
the Russian Federation, as well as for the executive organs of 
state power of federation components. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

