<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechnya Charges Moscow With Shielding Crime Groups </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK3004130094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 30 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> MK3004130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report in the "Provincial Chronicle" column] </F>
  [Text] Groznyy -- Chechnya Vice President Zelimkhan 
Yandarbiyev announced a possible meeting and signing of a treaty 
between the Russian Federation leadership and official Groznyy 
representatives. Mr. Yandarbiyev noted that "Elections in the 
Chechen state are possible only after a decision has been made 
by the leadership of the Ichkeria Republic, within the time 
frame established by the Constitution of Chechnya." 
  The head of the Chechnya security department has charged 
Russia's law enforcement bodies with criminals action aimed at 
undermining the republic's economy. In an official letter sent 
to the leadership of Russian Federation power structures, Sultan 
Geliskhanov reports that stable criminal groups, which for a 
long time have engaged in oil smuggling, are taking refuge in 
Russia. 
  The Crimean Republic has expressed a wish for comprehensive 
cooperation with the Chechen Republic. This is stated in a 
letter received by President Dudayev from the Crimean 
administration. The reaction by the Chechen leadership is so 
far unknown. 

</TEXT>

