<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Over 3,000 Attend May Day Rally in Nalchik </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Over 3,000 Attend May Day Rally in Nalchik </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105153394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1209 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0105153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] More than 3,000 people took part in the May-Day 
demonstration in Nalchik on Sunday. The demonstrators marched 
along the city's central street from the square commemorating 
the 400th anniversary of Kabarda's joining Russia over to Lenin 
Square. Among the demonstrators were Prime Minister of 
Kabardino-Balkaria Georgiy Cherkesov, Vice President Gennadiy 
Gubin and other leaders of the republic. 
  The meeting in front of the government building was 
addressed 
by President of Kabardino-Balkaria Valeriy Kokov, who said that 
ethnic peace and agreement had been preserved and that May-Day 
celebrations were marked by optimism and confidence in the 
future. He also said that the embezzlement of national property 
had been prevented, the labor potential saved and social support 
provided for pensioners, disabled people and low-incomes groups. 
  Speaking about the situation in the Russian Federation, 
Kokov 
said that the adoption of the new constitution last December had 
marked the beginning of a new process of sociopolitical 
stabilization. "The bitter fate of the Soviet Union, whose 
break up filled the hearts of million of people with pain, will 
not befell on the Russian Federation," he said. 
  He also welcomed the signing of the Civic Accord agreement 
as 
a stabilizing factor which meets the interests of the people, 
who are tired of political confrontation. 
  In conclusion, Kokov congratulated Christians on Easter and 
expressed hope that religious confessions will help strengthen 
the unity of Kabardino-Balkaria and preserve ethnic peace. 
  After the meeting festivities were held involving 
professional and amateur performers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

