<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Asks World To Help Solve Chernobyl Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Asks World To Help Solve Chernobyl Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004162294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1327 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3004162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk said Ukraine was 
bearing the whole brunt of problems caused by the Chernobyl 
disaster, "although the country which planted the Chernobyl bomb 
under Ukraine no longer exists." 
  Ukraine will be unable to solve those problems without the 
world community's assistance, Kravchuk said on Tuesday at a 
rally marking the eighth anniversary of the tragedy. 
  "We can understand those who demand that the Chernobyl 
Nuclear Power Plant be closed down immediately," he said, adding 
that Ukraine would need international assistance in that too. 
But Ukraine "cannot do without" nuclear plants, he told the 
rally, held outside the fire station whose personnel fought the 
fire at the Chernobyl plant on 26 April 1986. 
  Also on Tuesday, local activists of the international 
Greenpeace erected a symbolic earth mound to commemorate the 
Chernobyl victims. 
  Last year Ukraine's nuclear plants generated 33 pct (the 
Chernobyl plant 7 pct) of the country's electricity. 

</TEXT>

