<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Apologizes to Latvia for Stalinist Actions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Apologizes to Latvia for Stalinist Actions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004161494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1327 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3004161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Addressing journalists after the signing of 
Russian-Latvian documents in the Kremlin on Saturday, President 
Yeltsin apologized to the Latvians for anti-Latvian actions by 
Stalin's totalitarian regime. 
  "We declare that again. We condemn those actions against 
independent Latvia and its people," Yeltsin stressed. 
  Speaking in reply, Latvia's President Guntis Ulmanis voiced 
hope that Yeltsin's statement would help many Latvians to get 
over the prejudices piled up over the past decades in relations 
with Russia. 
  Asked by an INTERFAX correspondent about the outcome of 
bilateral talks, Yeltsin revealed that along with preparation 
for the signing ceremony he and Ulmanis had drawn up guidelines 
for economic accords with the view to endorse them. According 
to Yeltsin, there are 10 such drafts, including documents on 
free trade, on the most favoured status in trade, and on 
easy-term taxation. 
  In Yeltsin's words, a mixed working group will elaborate on 
these documents so that Russia's Premier Victor Chernomyrdin 
could sign them during a visit to Riga. However, it is too 
early to say when precisely he will go there, Yeltsin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

