<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin: Russia Not Pursuing Military Aims in Estonia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin: Russia Not Pursuing Military Aims in Estonia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004122694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1133 
GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Anna Melnikova, Yuriy </F>
Sizov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 30 Apr -- Russia is not pursuing any 
military aims or interests in Estonia, Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin said in the Kremlin today while answering journalists' 
questions after the signing of a package of Russian-Latvian 
agreements. 
  Russia intends to withdraw all troops from Estonia, but we 
want this to be done on a legal basis, as is already taking 
place in Russia's mutual relations with Lithuania and Latvia, 
Yeltsin stressed. In connection with this, he recalled that 
Russia was strictly observing the accords reached in Germany, 
and that Russian soldiers would leave this country by the end of 
the year. 
  If the Estonian side shows goodwill, it will have full 
consent from ours, Yeltsin said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

