<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Latvian President Ends Visit to Moscow, Leaves for Riga </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Latvian President Ends Visit to Moscow, Leaves for Riga </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004185194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English GMT 1807 GMT 30 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow 30 April TASS -- Latvian President Guntis 
Ulmanis ended his visit to Moscow and left for Riga late on 
Saturday. 
  During the visit Ulmanis and President Boris Yeltsin signed 
an agreement to withdraw Russian troops from Latvia by 31 August 
1994 and a number of agreements concerning the status of Russian 
servicemen in Latvia, members of their families and military 
pensioners. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS after the talks Yeltsin said 
that "Russian-Latvian documents signed today in the Kremlin were 
drawn up with full consent of both sides." 
  Ulmanis said the reached agreements aim at normalising 
relations between the two countries. He stressed he and Yeltsin 
reached "full understanding" on all issues included in the 
agenda of the talks. 
  Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs said that the 
agreement 
on economic cooperation and trade between Russia and Latvia is 
also practically ready and will facilitate the soonest possible 
implementation of the reached accords. Birkavs expressed the 
confidence that the agreement can be signed during Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin's upcoming visit to Latvia due to 
take place in the second half of May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

