<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Forces To Leave Latvia by 31 Aug </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Forces To Leave Latvia by 31 Aug </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004085294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0801 
GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004085294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Anna Melnikova and Yuriy </F>
Sizov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 30 Apr -- The Russian Armed Forces are to be 
withdrawn from the territory of the Republic of Latvia by 31 
August 1994. ITAR-TASS correspondents learned this during the 
course of talks between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and 
Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis. 
  Russia and Latvia will sign a treaty on conditions, 
deadlines, and the procedure for the complete withdrawal of the 
Russian Armed Forces from the territory of the Latvian Republic 
and their legal situation for the period of the withdrawal. The 
complete withdrawal of the Armed Forces includes all members of 
the Russian Armed Forces, members of their families and personal 
estate. 
  An integral part of the present treaty will also be an 
agreement on the status of the Skrunda radar station for the 
period of its functioning and dismantlement. 
  Agreements will be signed between the two countries on 
matters of social protection for military servicemen and members 
of their families temporarily resident on the territory of the 
Latvian Republic until their complete withdrawal, as well as 
matters of social protection for military pensioners and their 
families living on the territory of the Latvian Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

