<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Delegation Urges Lifting Sanctions Against Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Duma Delegation Urges Lifting Sanctions Against Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904154394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1514 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 29 April TASS -- "Obvious violation of the 
principle of equal responsibility in respect of the participants 
in Bosnian and Serb-Croatian conflicts leads to their 
exacerbation and hampers the beginning of serious peace talks." 
  Such was the conclusion made by an official delegation of 
Russian lawmakers from the State Duma (Russian parliament's 
lower house) on the results of their visit to the union Republic 
of Yugoslavia, Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The delegation prepared a communique on preliminary results 
of the visit, which was highlighted at a news conference on 
Friday [29 April]. 
  The lawmakers visited former Yugoslavia on 21-27 April with 
a 
view to working out proposals on settling the crisis. The 
delegation brought together representatives of all the State 
Duma factions. They visited Belgrade, Pale, Sarajevo (including 
its Moslem part), Vukovar, and Zagreb. 
  According to the communique, Russia "should make concerted 
efforts through the UN framework to cancel gradually sanctions 
against the union Republic of Yugoslavia, which are a serious 
manifestation of world community's unbalanced approach to the 
conflicting parties." 
  The lawmakers expressed particular concern about "actual 
information warfare against Serbs unleashed by the mass media." 
  Most of the members of the delegation believe that the 
Russian Foreign Ministry made mistakes in recognizing the 
unitary state of Bosnia-Herzegovina and in supporting unilateral 
sanctions adopted by UN against the union Republic of Yugoslavia. 
  According to Deputy Konstantin Zatulin, who represented the 
Party of Russian Unity and Accord, the delegates derived an 
impression from talking with UN representatives that the latter 
"are under tremendous pressure from NATO officers, who itch to 
resort to force in former Yugoslavia." 
  The delegates will present their conclusions at a plenary 
session of the State Duma scheduled for 11 May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

