<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Deputies Complete Observer Mission in RSA Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Deputies Complete Observer Mission in RSA Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904195394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1941 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Vladimir Korochantsev </F>
and Yuriy Pichugin] 
  [Text] Pretoria 29 April TASS -- A mission of Russian State 
Duma deputies in South Africa, where they observed the universal 
non-racial elections, has been completed. 
  Before leaving for Russia on Friday deputy group head A. 
Chilingarov told ITAR-TASS the voting was a historic stage in 
the life of South Africa divided in the recent past by racial 
barriers. 
  "We have visited many areas of residence of white and black 
communities and talked to representatives of various political 
parties, officials and average voters," he said. "We were most 
impressed by activeness of the population, enthusiasm of 
Africans who have been given the right to vote for the first 
time, and the atmosphere of friendliness in meters-long lines to 
the polling stations." 
  In his opinion, some drawbacks in the elections were caused 
by the absence of registration lists, which resulted in a sharp 
shortage of ballot sheets. This may give a reason for doubts in 
case of any disputes. 
  The Russian observer mission included V. Sheynis, G. 
Seleznev 
and I. Novitskaya. In their opinion, the South African 
elections signify a transition from confrontation to cooperation 
and show the will of representatives of all races and political 
convictions to national reconciliation and solution of 
disputable issues exclusively by peaceful civilized methods. 
  The parliament members noted genuine interest of South 
Africans in Russia and their striving to develop fruitful and 
friendly relations with it. 

</TEXT>

