<H3> <TI>   Peacekeepers Airlifted to Yugoslavia as Part of Rotation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peacekeepers Airlifted to Yugoslavia as Part of Rotation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904152894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1303 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A further 227 Russian peacekeepers complete with 
satellite communication equipment has been airlifted aboard two 
airforce transport planes from a military airport in Ryazan to 
ex-Yugoslavia, military officials told Interfax in Moscow. The 
operation is part of the rotation of the Russian contingent of 
the United Nations Protection Force there. 
  As many as 600 servicemen of the 1,500-strong Russian 
peacekeeping force deployed in the former Yugoslavia are to be 
replaced in April. 
  It is now known that many of the peacekeepers who served a 
term of six months and earned $6,000 have bought cars and will 
be travelling home by road. 

</TEXT>

