<H3> <TI>   UN Assures Moscow its Views on Bosnia Will Be Considered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Assures Moscow its Views on Bosnia Will Be Considered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004164394 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1530 GMT 
30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] We have just this minute received some information 
from the Russian Federation Foreign Ministry. It says: By 
continuing to play an active role in settling the situation in 
former Yugoslavia, Russian diplomacy, along with its five 
partners in Yugoslavia -- Russia, Great Britain, Spain, the 
United States, and France -- enabled important progress to be 
made in strengthening the safe havens regime in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The Security Council has proposed that the UN secretary 
general come forward with concrete recommendations on this issue 
by 10 May. The UN Secretariat has assured the Russian 
representative that the Russian proposals put forward earlier on 
this will be taken into account when these recommendations are 
being worked out, in addition to the information in the letter 
from the Security Council chairman. 
  It is the unanimous view of the sides looking for a 
settlement that the strengthening of the safe havens regime will 
push forward significantly settlement of the main tasks today, 
being tackled by the Russian, the United States, EC, and the UN 
contact group. These are to achieve an end to all military 
activity and bring the conflicting sides back to the negotiating 
table. 
  This information is from the Russian Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

