<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Soskovets Discussed Writing Off Syrian Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies Soskovets Discussed Writing Off Syrian Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904151194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1303 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A Russian Government official has denied media 
reports that Russian Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets, 
during his recent visit to Syria, had discussed writing off part 
of that country's debt to Russia. 
  The matter was not brought up at all at the Damascus talks, 
Sergey Sidorkov, head of the Russian Government's Department for 
Defense Industries and Defense Conversion, who accompanied 
Soskovets on his Syrian trip, told INTERFAX. Moreover, Syria 
agreed to pay for its orders to Russian enterprises in advance, 
he said. But all such matters -- the volume of, and schedules 
for, supplies to Syria, including those of spares for armaments 
already sold to Damascus, payment procedures, etc., -- will be 
handled by a special intergovernmental commission, he said. 
  Sidorkov said no concrete plans for Russian arms sales to 
Syria had been negotiated during Soskovets's visit. 
  The bulk of Syria's $10-billion debt to Russia is in arrears 
for weapons bought from the Soviet Union in the 1970's and 
1980's. Syria is willing to pay the debt to Russia as the 
Soviet Union's legal successor. 

</TEXT>

