<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   May Day Communist Rally Gathers Thousands in Yereven </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    May Day Communist Rally Gathers Thousands in Yereven </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105193394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1751 
GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan, 1 May--May Day was marked in Armenia for 
the first time in several years. The central rally was held in 
Yerevan under the flags of the USSR and the Armenian Soviet 
Socialist Republic and with the portraits of Lenin. According 
to various estimates, from 10,000 to 60,000 people took part in 
it. They gathered on the square in front of the opera theater 
under the slogans: "A New Union With Russia is the Only 
Salvation for Armenia" and "No to Capital". Sergey Badalyan, 
the leader of the Armenian Communist Party, called for early 
presidential and parliamentary elections in Armenia and for 
Armenia to join the ruble zone. He expressed solidarity with 
the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, having said that 
"Zyuganov's party fully controls the political situation in 
Russia today." 

</TEXT>

