<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Backs Constitutional Referendum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Backs Constitutional Referendum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   944K1124B Yerevan RESPUBLIKA ARMENIYA in Russian 26 Apr 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> 944K1124B </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan RESPUBLIKA ARMENIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [News department report: "Levon Ter-Petrosyan: `Constitution </F>
Is an Accord'"] 
  [Text] Armenian Republic President L. Ter-Petrosyan spoke 
yesterday in the parliament. The nation's existence--this is 
what national accord means, said the president. The nation has 
always been united by common concerns, customs, ideas of the 
future. Disagreements, on the other hand, existed between 
political forces. Nor does Levon Ter-Petrosyan recognize such a 
notion as national ideology. In his opinion, in a democratic 
society it is impossible to unite democracy around one idea, 
since the final outcome may be fascism, as world experience has 
proven. Armenia must have a national program of democratization 
and development that, in addition to traits mentioned in its 
title, must be universal and humanitarian. 
  "A constitution is an accord! All citizens, as well as 
different political forces in Armenia, must obey it," said 
Ter-Petrosyan. 
  The president believes that a referendum is the most 
effective way to adopt the basic law. He expressed certainty 
that the Armenian people will adopt their constitution and thus 
remove tension in the sociopolitical life of the country. The 
president said once again that a violent change of 
authority--the way it had happened in Azerbaijan, Georgia, and 
Tajikistan--is impossible in Armenia. Further on L. 
Ter-Petrosyan proposed his plan for pulling out of the crisis. 
First: The parliament expresses confidence in either the 
Constitutional Commission's draft or the draft of "the six" and 
without discussion votes on submitting one of the drafts to a 
referendum vote. Second: If this does not happen, both drafts 
are put to a referendum and then a second round of the 
referendum may be needed. Third: In the event the draft of six 
parties passes, the president and the government resign. Fourth: 
If the Constitutional Commission's draft passes, new elections 
for president and National Assembly are held. And fifth: Before 
this session ends, the parliament must adopt a law on Armenian 
Republic citizenship and elections to the republic's National 
Assembly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60853 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_p_94004" </HT>


