<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Presents Plan for Refugees' Repatriation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General Presents Plan for Refugees' Repatriation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904131194 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 29 Apr 94 
Single Edition p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM2904131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Georgia: Resolving the Fate of </F>
Refugees"] 
  [Text] Judging by many reports in the local press, the 
mechanism for returning refugees to their native regions and 
guarantees of their safety have become a bone of contention at 
the Georgian-Abkhazian talks which are being conducted with 
Russian mediation and under the auspices of the United Nations. 
Putting forward the Georgian plan to resolve these problems, 
Major General Vladimir Chikovani, commander of the republic's 
Internal Troops and member of the Georgian delegation at the 
Geneva talks, remarked in conversation with an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent that the Russian side is taking a constructive 
stance in Geneva and showing its committment to bringing peace 
to Abkhazia and resolving the fate of hundreds of thousands of 
civilians forcibly expelled from their native lands. The 
Georgian plan also met with the support of UN representatives at 
these talks. 
  The main thrust of the Georgian plan, the general said, is 
the need to monitor the withdrawal of all armed formations with 
their weapons and combat equipment from all the lines of active 
confrontation in the conflict zone and from all the regions of 
Abkhazia to which it is planned to return the refugees. 
  The Georgian plan is based exclusively on the principles and 
provisions of the quadrilateral agreements, and stems from the 
logic of the nonresumption of military operations and the 
termination of the conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

