<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demonstrators in Moscow Rally Voice Demands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demonstrators in Moscow Rally Voice Demands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105102794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0946 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0105102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Karlov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 1 TASS -- The orators at a meeting in the 
centre of Moscow sponsored by the Moscow Federation of Labour 
Unions demanded that the government pay up on its salary 
obligations, index salaries to the inflation rate, give state 
subsidies to the agricultural sector, get rid of unemployment, 
establish strict control over retail trade, and do much more. 
  As always happens with such demonstrators, there was no lack 
of anti-president and anti-government slogans. All the speakers 
finished their appearances with hurrahs for international 
workers' solidarity day. However, in contrast to previous 
years, there were no representatives of the international 
proletariat at the meeting. 
  The Moscow Federation of Labour Unions collected about ten 
thousand demonstrators for its march from Triumfalnaya (Triumph) 
Square to the Manezh just across from the Kremlin, which started 
at nine a.m. this morning. By the time the procession reached 
the meeting place, it had lost half its participants. Dominant 
were representatives from almost all the trade unions, the 
Communist Party of the Russian Federation, and guests from many 
Russian regions. 
  The meeting was over at 10:30, by which time the square had 
practically emptied. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

