<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `About 25,000' Reportedly Take Part </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `About 25,000' Reportedly Take Part </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105101594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0916 
GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yekaterina Zhilyakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 1 May -- Representatives of trade unions who 
held a festive rally in Manezh Square in the capital today on 
the occasion of the International Day of Solidarity of the 
Working People stated their readiness to defend the economic and 
social interests of the working people. 
  We are for accord and civic peace but not at the expense of 
the working people and not at the expense of depriving common 
people of their rights, Mikhail Nagaytsev, chairman of the 
Moscow Federation of Trade Unions [MFTU] said opening the rally. 
According to him, on the eve of May Day about 2.5 million 
people signed demands circulated by the MFTU, which will be 
passed to the government. Among them are demands to introduce 
articles to the legislation of the Russian Federation on the 
accountability of those guilty of delaying salary payments, to 
adopt a state employment program for the population, and to step 
up the work of law-enforcement bodies in the fight against crime 
and corruption. 
  A resolution adopted by the rally -- in which about 25,000 
people took part according to Nagaytsev -- notes that a solution 
to the present crisis, which is leading to the country's 
impoverishment, is possible only if the level of unemployment is 
halted, there is state support for Russia's producers, and 
tariff agreements are fulfilled. 
  War and labor veterans and members of the Russian Communist 
Party took part in the rally in Manezh Square together with 
representatives of 42 trade union organizations from Moscow city 
and oblast, St. Petersburg, Nizhniy Novgorod, Voronezh, 
Smolensk, Kostroma, Tula, Kaluga, and other towns. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

