<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin's Office Opts for Faxnet Communications System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin's Office Opts for Faxnet Communications System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904124394 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1920 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM2904124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast: Video report by Vadim Budnikov, </F>
identified by caption] 
  [Text] Fewer than 50 percent of intercity faxes reach 
their addressees in Russia. The reason for this are poor 
communications channels and antediluvian equipment at most 
telephone exchanges. Ordinary people simply have to somehow 
live with this. But this situation is totally unacceptable in 
the case of the president's office or the government apparatus. 
Official information must be transmitted instantly, otherwise 
normal administration of the country becomes impossible. This 
would be particularly dangerous during an exacerbation of the 
political situation. 
  [B. Kosenkov, spokesman of the president's office, 
identified 
by caption] This is why the president's office has opted for 
the Faxnet network. This system makes it possible to transmit 
information to remote areas promptly, speedily, and with a high 
degree of reliability. 
  [Budnikov] A purely Russian feature of this modern 
technology is the utilization of the channels of the former 
Iskra party-economic communications system which links some 500 
cities in our country. [video shows office equipment including 
Faxnet LAN-mailer and a diagram] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

