<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Republican Party Leader on Signing of Accord Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Republican Party Leader on Signing of Accord Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904142894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1051 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 29 TASS -- "If the Russian Republican 
Party have not signed the Social Accord Treaty, this would mean 
its complete political isolation and sliding to recalcitrant 
opposition", deputy of the Duma Vladimir Lysenko, co-chairman of 
the party, told a news conference on Friday. Lysenko views the 
signing of the treaty by Russia's political elite as an 
important step toward civic accord and a breakthrough in public 
conscience. 
  Lysenko hopes there will be no more revolutions in Russia. 
Society embarks of a period of evolutional development. He 
believes the treaty may offer an opportunity of political 
stability in a country for at least two years. Political 
competition will be manifested in parliamentary and presidential 
elections, not through violent non-parliamentary actions. 
  Lysenko apparently decided to give the news conference 
because of the situation that formed as a result of the 
Republican Party's joining the treaty while leaders of the group 
Yabloko in which the party is included refused to do so. It 
should be noted that representatives of the Republican Party 
were elected to the state duma on the ticket of Yabloko bloc. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

