<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders Clarify Role of Democratic Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Leaders Clarify Role of Democratic Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904180694 Moscow RIA in English 1609 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 29, RIA -- The Democratic Russia 
movement intends to become a party of the same name, initiators 
of the organising committee of a federal party, movement 
co-chairmen Lev Ponomarev and Gleb Yakunin said today. 
  Ponomarev told a RIA correspondent by telephone that the two 
other co-chairmen of the movement -- Ilya Zaslavskiy and 
Grigoriy Tomchin -- joined Yegor Gaydar's newly created party 
Russia's Choice, while the position of the fifth co-chairwoman 
-- Galina Starovoitova -- remains unknown because she is abroad. 
  The split, says a statement issued by Ponomarev and Yakunin 
today, was caused by the fact that Democratic Russia does not 
want to become an organisation arranging mass actions for the 
Russia's Choice party, as the Soviet trade unions did for the 
CPSU. 
  In Ponomarev's view, "in three to four months it will be 
possible to think of registering the party, but before that a 
lot of work has to be done in the regions". 
  "The Democratic Russia party will be a rival to Gaydar's 
Russia's Choice, but we do not expect ideological differences 
between the two related parties," noted Ponomarev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60888 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_b_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Dynamic Center' Needed To Implement Accord Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Dynamic Center' Needed To Implement Accord Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904124994 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 29 Apr 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2904124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Presidential Council Member Aleksey Salmin </F>
under the general heading "Treaty on Accord Is Open Book": 
"Mechanism for Implementation Necessary, Presidential Council 
Member Aleksey Salmin Believes"] 
  [Text] An immense amount of work has been done on the 
draft Treaty on Civil Accord and various parties' interests have 
been taken into account in it. Unfortunately, this has not 
always come about harmoniously and there are problems in the 
text itself. However, the main point is not that it has been 
produced but the way this document will "work." 
  After all, this important document should be "built into" a 
certain system of relations, therefore its fate is still not 
determined even if its signing goes off smoothly. 
  The problem for the accord's potential participants, all 
branches and centers of power on Russian territory, is for the 
document to actually "begin to work." This means that there 
should be a certain mechanism for its implementation. Such a 
mechanism could be a genuine accord in parliament, in 
particular, between several factions. A broad nationwide accord 
is not even necessary but a more local one so as to adopt a 
package of essential laws connected with security (on the whole, 
personal security), and other laws, in particular, on economic 
reform, as well as criminal and civil codes, and much else as 
concerns legislation. 
  For this it is necessary that, on the basis of the treaty, 
efficient coalitions are formed in both of parliament's 
chambers, and it is also, of course, necessary for a genuine 
accord to exist between Moscow and the Federation components. 
  So, a dynamic center is necessary to implement the accord so 
that it does not remain only on paper but becomes a fact of 
political life. Such a dynamic center could take the form of 
permanent consultations at the highest level between 
representatives of the various power structures. It would be 
better if this is a permanent working group with a high level of 
cooperation. Because, despite the fact that an important and 
essential step has been taken, what is most important -- 
precisely that which lies at this document's heart -- still lies 
ahead. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60889 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_b_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chubays on Benefits of Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chubays on Benefits of Foreign Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105150994 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 0721 GMT 
1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The next subject in our Panorama slot may 
possibly come as a surprise. After all, two whole months remain 
before the so-called zero hour -- two whole months before the 
period for using our privatization vouchers ends. Some people 
may have forgotten, or some people may not fully remember the 
mechanism for using our vouchers and the legal mechanism for the 
privatization process. It was these matters that our 
correspondent Nikolay Filippov put to Anatoliy Chubays, the 
Russian deputy prime minister. 
  [Begin recording] [Filippov] Anatoliy Borisovich, what do we 
need to do in the remaining two months? 
  [Chubays] It is a short period of time and many people have 
not yet managed to properly ponder their next moves. [passage 
omitted] 
  At present we estimate that there are at least 10 million, 
people who have not yet taken their final decision. [passage 
omitted] On 1 July the period of validity of the privatization 
vouchers expires. They need to be used before then. [passage 
omitted] Our figures show that the involvement of foreigners in 
the voucher privatization process has been very insignificant. 
In fewer than 10 percent of cases has foreign capital been 
involved in the voucher privatization process itself. There is 
no sense therefore in saying that our homeland is being sold off 
for a song. [passage omitted] 
  We now see, especially over the past few months, a sharp 
increase in the involvement of foreign capital at the 
post-voucher stage. [passage omitted] When I see that at the 
post-voucher stage many major firms such as Siemens, Proctor and 
Gamble, and Philip Morris are investing tens of billions of 
dollars in Russian enterprises, it signifies for me an upsurge 
in Russian enterprises and the start of a growth in dividends. 
[passage omitted] Dividends grow and at the same time the 
Russian economy gains, because it means increased production, 
new jobs, and the start of an emergence from the crisis that we 
are now in. Indeed, we are starting to emerge through the 
inflow of investments that have been forthcoming only because 
private enterprises and joint-stock companies are concerned. 
This is a guarantee of a real start to an upsurge of the 
Russian economy as a whole. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60890 </DOCNO>
