<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin: State To Cut Support for Mass Media </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin: State To Cut Support for Mass Media </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK3004074094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 30 Apr 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK3004074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Unattributed report under the "In Brief" rubric: 
"Orenburg"] 
  [Text] "The state does need the press and television, but 
not in the amounts in which they currently exist," Russian 
Federation Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin told journalists 
in Orenburg, where he arrived to attend festivities on the 
occasion of the 250th anniversary of Orenburg Guberniya's 
formation. The premier pointed out that the state would 
maintain a number of newspapers and television channels, but 
this would not apply to all existing mass media. According to 
the head of government, the system of state support for 
newspapers and television will be preserved only during a 
transition period. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60901 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_b_94031" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Backs Draft Law Protecting Press </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Backs Draft Law Protecting Press </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904105194 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 29 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2904105194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Igor Korolkov report: "Chernomyrdin Intends To Ease the </F>
Lot of the Press"] 
  [Text] The prime minister has supported a draft law on 
state protection, Boris Mironov, chairman of the Russian 
Federation Committee for the Press, reported at a press 
conference, the state protection in question being applied to 
the mass media, book production, and those sectors -- the 
printing and paper industries -- which provide them with 
services. 
  Under the draft law, among other things, the printing 
facilities of the mass media are exempt from the payment of 
customs duties for the import of paper, printing equipment, and 
spare parts which are not produced in Russia. Publishing houses 
are also exempt from customs duties for the products they 
export. The mass media will receive a 50 percent discount on 
postal, telegraph, and telephone communication charges. 
  If the draft law proposed by the Committee for the Press is 
passed by the State Duma, it will cost the state exchequer R1 
billion. Unlike Chernomyrdin and the Ministry of the Economy, 
which have supported it, the Finance Ministry is against. This 
is understandable: It fears that other sectors will also argue 
their exceptional status and demand similar concessions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

