<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Pay Raise Could Herald `Political Events' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Pay Raise Could Herald `Political Events' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904103894 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 1-4 May 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM2904103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Igor Chernyak report: "Will Pay Go Up? If Only We Knew </F>
What It Will Entail..."] 
  [Text] According to KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA's information, 
Boris Yeltsin intends to sign within the next few days a 
decision on a further increase in the salaries of servicemen in 
the Russian Armed Forces -- by 50 percent, so it is supposed. 
One could only congratulate officers and generals in this 
connection, if it were not for one "but." 
  This is not the first time the president has demonstrated 
his 
concern for the Army. But, by a strange coincidence, similar 
decisions have hitherto been adopted on the eve of a possible 
exacerbation of the political situation in the country. For 
example, before the referendum of April 1993, when the troops 
were paid "arrears" of pay and more than 150 generalships were 
conferred on top officers. The situation was repeated shortly 
before the president's "strategic fall offensive," when the 
Ministry of Finance suddenly and "unexpectedly" paid servicemen 
the salaries for July-September, which had been delayed, with a 
coefficient of 1.8. At the time, comments appeared in 
newspapers in this connection, and there was talk of a special 
plan to influence the Army and a desire to boost its loyalty to 
the authorities on the eve of important political events. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

