<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Candidate Moroz Rejects Election Postponement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Candidate Moroz Rejects Election Postponement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105125194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1150 
GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS corresponedents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Notv, 1 May -- Aleksandr Moroz (Socialist Party), 
candidate for the Ukrainian presidency, is categorically against 
postponing the date for electing the head of state: I will do 
everything to have the election take place on the scheduled 
date, he told ITAR-TASS in an interview today. 
  You will recall that Leonid Kravchuk has appealed to 
parliament with an initiative to transfer the date of the 
presidential election from 26 June to a later date. This was 
supported the other day by 120 deputies in the Supreme Council. 
  Combining with the communists and the Peasants' Party in a 
single bloc, the Socialist Party now has 36 percent of the seats 
in parliament. If it is remembered that Ukrainian communist 
leader Petr Symonenko gave up his presidential candidacy the 
other day, then Aleksandr Morozov has a substantial chance of 
winning in the presidential marathon; but for this to happen he 
needs to collect 100,000 voters' signatures for his initial 
official registration as candidate for the post of president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

