<DOCNO> FBIS4-60920 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov084_f_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Tatar Leader Interviewed on Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Tatar Leader Interviewed on Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904170094 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1240 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Simferopol -- In an exclusive interview with a UNIAN 
correspondent the other day, Mustafa Dzhemilev, chairman of the 
Majlis of the Crimean Tatar People, stated that in the event of 
a Ukrainian presidential election being held, Crimean Tatars 
would "definitely be against Leonid Kuchma." 
  "We have quite often discussed our problems with 
Interregional Bloc of Reforms [MBR] representatves -- and 
Volodymyr Hrynyov in particular. He tends to view Crimean Tatars 
as a Crimean ethnic minority. So if the choice is to be made 
between Leonid Kuchma and Leonid Kravchuk, we would prefer the 
latter. As for Ivan Plyushch, we have a bone to pick with him, 
too." 
  Forecasting the activity of the Crimean Tatar group in the 
Crimean Supreme Council, Mustafa Dzhemilev said they were 
offered cooperation by Rossiya bloc group members but that it 
was unacceptable. As for the Communists, the Majlis leader 
said, "we can hear their secretary, Leonid Hrach, making a lot 
of proposals that are not too bad. The Communists, however, 
have always been saying one thing and, once in power, doing 
another." 
  Mustafa Dzhemilev said that Yuriy Meshkov had suggested they 
should back Serhiy Tsekov, former Ukrainian people's deputy and 
supporter of the Rossiya bloc, as an appointee to the post of 
Crimean parliamentary speaker, with a Crimean Tatar 
representative then to be offered the post of deputy Supreme 
Council chairman. The Majlis chairman said: "We find such 
compromises deplorable and shall not accept them." The most 
fair thing to do, in his words, would be to elect Refat 
Chubarov, head of the Crimean Tatar deputies group, to the post 
of Crimean parliamentary speaker. However, his candidacy will 
not be put forward as he will stand no chance of winning. The 
Crimean Tatars are most likely not to back anyone to this post. 
  Mustafa Dzhemilev expressed the hope that the Crimean Tatars 
would succeed in appealing against the 14-seat quota granted to 
them by the previous Crimean Supreme Council. Yuriy Meshkov's 
statement that "the granting of even this quota was [former 
Crimean parliamentary speaker] Mykola Bahrov's error," was 
described by Mustafa Dzhemilev as nonpopulist and as an attempt 
to exert pressure on the Crimean Tatars. He added that the 
Crimean president's tactics might become the beginning of the 
end of his presidency." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

