<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Indicates President Kuchma Favored in Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Indicates President Kuchma Favored in Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004160494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1441 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3004160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine's former Prime-Minister Leonid Kuchma stands 
the best chance to win the presidential race. According to the 
sociological service Sotcis-Gullap, 18 percent of the voters 
favored his candidacy in March. In December 16.6 percent of the 
voters did so. 
  The service polled a total of 1,200 people older than 15 
throughout Ukraine to find out that Viacheslav Chernovil (10 
percent in March and 9.1 percent in December) and President 
Leonid Kravchuk (11 percent in March and 16.5 in December) 
emerged as two other frontrunners. 
  The People's Rukh movement decided to refrain from running 
its own presidential nominee. 

</TEXT>

