<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communist Candidate Withdraws From Presidential Race </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communist Candidate Withdraws From Presidential Race </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105155094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1530 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0105155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Viktor Demidenko, Mikhail </F>
Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev 1 May TASS--leader of Ukrainian Communists Petr 
Simonenko, running for the Ukrainian presidency, withdrew his 
candidature following a two-hour confidential meeting with 
Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk, a high-ranking official of 
the Ukrainian president's administration told ITAR-TASS today. 
However, he declined to give details of the meeting, saying 
that it was "secret." 
  It was not ruled out that Simonenko's step was a result of a 
thoroughly planned policy of opposition to the Ukrainian 
President Leonid Kravchuk and was aimed at consolidating voters 
in favour of a leader of a Socialist Party, Aleksandr Morozov. 
The move was apparently made to take advantage of the obvious 
disappointment of the Ukrainian population in the present 
leadership and its failure to ensure normal life in the country. 
  Apart from Leonid Kravchuk, taking part in the presidential 
race are Ukrainian Parliament Speaker Ivan Plyushch, Prime 
Minister Leonid Kuchma, Vice-Premiers Vladimir Lanovoy and 
Viktor Pinzenik, Education Minister Petro Talanchuk and one of 
the leaders of the Ukrainian Union of Entrepreneurs, Valeriy 
Babich. 
  Ivan Plyushch is said to stand the best chance of being 
elected as a supporter of concentrating executive power in the 
hands of one person within a system of soviets as a form of 
state system. 
  If Kravchuk fails to postpone elections, he will find it 
difficult to remain in his post. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

