<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma: Reform Crucial for Better Ties With West </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma: Reform Crucial for Better Ties With West </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004161794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1327 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3004161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During the Ukrainian Former Prime Minister Leonid 
Kuchma's visit to U.S. earlier this month, U.S. Administration 
officials repeatedly stressed that Russia should stay Ukraine's 
chief strategic partner. 
  Kuchma, currently leading the Ukrainian Union of 
Industrialists and Businessmen, met during his one week tour of 
the United States with Vice-President Albert Gore, the Commerce 
Secretary's Assistant Andrew Summers, and a number of eminent 
senators. 
  "This trip has changed my attitude to U.S. lawmakers," 
Kuchma 
said. 
  In his words, American Administration officials regard 
Ukraine as a state rather than single out any Ukrainian leader. 
  He said that during his meeting with the International 
Monetary Fund's President Camdessus, the IMF leader made it 
clear that the Foundation will not help Ukraine unless it sees a 
leadership that means business rather than words there. 
  "If people in East and West alike see positive processes 
underway, they will rally around them," said Kuchma, who is a 
registered candidate to the Ukrainian presidency. 
  Presidential elections in Ukraine will take place on 26 
June. 

</TEXT>

