<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yelstin Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yelstin Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004123794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1027 
GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Anna Melnikova and Yuriy </F>
Sizov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 30 Apr -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin 
has declared in his interview to an ITAR-TASS correspondent 
after the ceremony in which a package of bilateral documents 
were signed: "The Russian-Latvian documents signed today in the 
Kremlin have been elaborated with the full consent by the both 
sides." 
  The head of the Russian state said that "as a whole, five 
documents have been signed: the Treaty and four agreements in 
which, in particular, the protection of servicemen was 
determined and the question of pensioners and former servicemen 
was solved." 
  Boris Yeltsin paid special attention to the treaty signed by 
him and Guntis Ulmanis, which ensured the withdrawal of Russian 
troops from the territory of Latvia. He said that "the final 
date of the withdrawal was determined to be 31 August." In 
addition he said that "the Russian side will try to do this as 
soon as possible because we want children of the servicemen to 
go to school in Russia already this 1 September." 
  The president also said that during the negotiations the 
delegations of the both countries "worked on about 10 economic 
documents as well." In this connection he underlined that "the 
presidents of the two countries have reached an agreement that 
the questions on free trade, the regime of the most favored 
nations on a mutual and equal basis, taxation, tariffs, and 
duties will be prepared by a special group and Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin will visit Riga where the signing 
of these documents will take place." 
  Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis answered a question by the 
ITAR-TASS correspondent and said that in one of the documents 
signed today "we were talking about the regime of the most 
favored nations between the two countries." He believes that 
"this is a very valuable achievement." He said that 
entrepreneurs of the both countries can now breathe freely 
because, speaking frankly, the politics "minded its own 
business, and the economy suffered from that." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

