  [Text] All last night, Ukrainian national television was 
broadcasting Easter services from churches of various religious 
confessions, while this morning the Socialist Party called on 
people to attend an officially sanctioned May Day rally and 
march to the Lenin monument to lay flowers. 
  At this moment there are three demonstrations in progress in 
Moscow. They are being organized by the Federation of Trade 
Unions, the Moscow Labor [Trudovaya Moskva] Movement, the 
Liberal Patriotic Party of Rebirth, and a bloc of communist 
parties. 
  Today, for the first of time in recent years, International 
Labor Day is being celebrated in Yerevan. The workforces of 
dozens of Yerevan's enterprises and institutions will turn out 
for a rally in the city. 
  An unsanctioned May Day rally is planned to be held on the 
central square of Bishkek by the Civic Council [Grazhdanskiy 
sovet]. This Kyrgyz public organization was set up two months 
ago under the aegis of the republic's legal rights movement to 
defend the rights of pensioners and the needy. 

