<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSCE To Place Observers in Nagorno-Karabakh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CSCE To Place Observers in Nagorno-Karabakh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105123694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1057 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0105123694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Talks on ways of settling the Karabakh conflict 
between the Karabakh leaders and the CSCE's Minsk group, led by 
Swedish diplomat Matias Mosberg, ended in Stepanakert on 
Saturday. 
  The Karabakh Foreign Ministry's press service informed 
Interfax that the main accent was put on mechanisms of excluding 
combat operations. To quote a representative of the press 
service, the delegation members stated that they would be able 
to place their observers three days after the conclusion of a 
long-term cease-fire agreement between the conflicting parties. 
  The negotiating parties also agreed not to adopt documents 
unconfirmed by real mechanisms of ruling out combat operations, 
and emphasized the importance of dovetailing the peace efforts 
of the CSCE and Russia. They also noted that certain steps had 
been made in this direction. 
  On the same day, CSCE military experts and the Karabakh 
commanders discussed military-technical problems pertaining to 
the location of observers in the zone of combat operations. 

</TEXT>

