<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Welcomed in Former Zviadist Region </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Welcomed in Former Zviadist Region </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904205194 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1900 GMT 
29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2904205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 29 April Georgian Head of State Eduard 
Shevardnadze made a brief visit to western Georgia. Here is 
Mikhail Mamulashvili reporting from Tbilisi: 
  [Mamulashvili] The main aim of Eduard Shevardnadze's visit 
to 
the western part of the republic was the desire to see for 
himself the state of affairs in the regions. This time, the 
head of state visited two rayons - Zugdidskiy and 
Tsalendzhikhskiy - which until recently were at the center of 
the Zviadist movement. 
  You will recall that it was here that the main events during 
the armed confrontation between government troops and armed 
supporters of the ex-president took place. The last time 
Shevardnadze was in Tsalendzhikha was two years ago. Back then 
he was obliged to endure reproaches and insults from people who 
considered Zviad Gamsakhurdia the only legitimate leader of the 
country. 
  On 29 April, things were different. The press service of the 
Georgian head of state informed me that Shevardnadze was given 
the warm welcome typically accorded by the inhabitants of that 
region. He met with the inhabitants of Tsalendzhikha, the heads 
of the local administration, representatives of the 
intelligentsia and local workers. 
  Speaking to the inhabitants of Tsalendzhikha, Shevardnadze 
stressed that Georgia is now going through a bad patch. We want 
to build a democratic state and that's why we all have to work 
instead of sitting down with our arms folded. 
  Touching on the situation in Abkhazia -- and inhabitants of 
Tsalendzhikha are particularly anxious about this question since 
their rayon borders Abkhazia and there are a large number of 
refugees in Tsalendzhikha itself -- Shevardnadze said that all 
matters and problems connected with that region would in all 
probability be solved in the near future. 
  The head of state was accompanied on his trip to western 
Georgia by Vakhtang Goguadze, speaker of the Georgian 
parliament, Prime Minster Otar Patatsia, and other officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

