<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plesetsk Test Range Marks 30th Anniversary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plesetsk Test Range Marks 30th Anniversary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904143394 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM2904143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast: Video report by S. Sokolova, </F>
identified by caption] 
  [Text] [Sokolova over video of truck-mounted missile 
travelling down a forest track] The Plesetsk test range is 30 
years old. Since the disintegration of the Union it is the only 
Russian test range from which satellites as well as missiles can 
be launched. Incidentally, last year the world's first 
communications satellite was launched into orbit from here 
aboard an ICBM. 
  The latest missile systems have been tested here. Four of 
them now form the main component of the Russian missile forces 
and are used for alert duty. 
  Under START II, the Plesetsk computer and information center 
is processing and analyzing telemetric information on both its 
own and the U.S. launches. The United States, in turn, receives 
all the requisite information about our missile systems. 
  According to specialists, Plesetsk is the most hardworking 
test range in the world. Up to 70 percent of the launches of 
various satellites and rockets [raketa] carried out in the world 
take place here. True, as from this year the number of launches 
has sharply decreased. The reasons for this are many, but the 
main one is the shortage of funds. This is why commercial 
satellites will also be launched from Plesetsk in the future. 
Fortunately, applications from Russian and Western companies 
have already been received. [video shows various closeups of 
truck-mounted missiles on forest track, soldiers changing 
equipment, views of computer center equipment, aerial view of 
Plesetsk area from helicopter] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

