<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tiraspol Women Ask Yeltsin Not To Withdraw 14th Army </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tiraspol Women Ask Yeltsin Not To Withdraw 14th Army </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3004194594 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1330 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3004194594 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tiraspol BASAPRESS, 30/4/1994 -- The Dniester 
Republic Women's Union (TWU), which is considered an extreme 
branch of the separatist movement in eastern Moldova, sent a 
message to Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev accusing General Aleksandr Lebed [commander of the 
14th Russian Army stationed in Dniester] of attempting to 
liquidate the self-proclaimed Dniester Republic. The message 
says that if Lebed ignores the Dniester legislation on 
Tiraspol's right to possess the 14th Army's property, the women 
will enchain themselves arm in arm with their children to 
prevent the evacuation of the Russian military troops and 
equipment from the Dniester region. The TWU asks Yeltsin to 
dismiss General Lebed as the 14th Army's commander. It also 
demands Russia's recognition of the self-proclaimed Dniester 
Republic. The TWU warns Yeltsin not to use the Dniester region 
"as a medium of exchange in political games." 

</TEXT>

