<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev, Uzbek, Kazakh Leaders Meet 29-30 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev, Uzbek, Kazakh Leaders Meet 29-30 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105102394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0740 
GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Yarushin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 1 May -- This morning, the apparatus of 
Presidents Askar Akayev and Islam Karimov confirmed to an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent that the heads of state of Kirghizia 
[Kyrgyzstan], Uzbekistan, and Kazakhstan held a meeting on 29-30 
April in the town of Karakol on the shore of Lake Issyk-Kul in 
Kyrgyzstan. The apparatus categorically refused to give details 
of the meeting, saying it was of a confidential nature. 
However, it was learned in a telephone conversation with a 
representative of Karimov's administration that a communique was 
signed on the results of the meeting. 
  ITAR-TASS has learned that the meeting in Karakol was 
devoted 
to the problems of creating an effective mechanism for a single 
economic zone in the region. Observers are expressing the 
supposition that they were discussing the possibility of a 
regional transformation of the idea of creating a Eurasian 
union. We remind you that in Moscow on 29 March Nursultan 
Nazarbayev proposed the creation of a new association of CIS 
member states -- a Eurasian union. At that time he said that if 
the idea did not find sufficient support in the CIS, a Eurasian 
union could be joined by individual states. 
  Nazarbayev's idea of a Eurasian union of states proposes the 
formation of supranational bodies to coordinate economic, 
defense, and foreign policy; the formation of a single 
parliament and councils of defense and foreign ministers; and 
the introduction of common citizenship. 
  The idea of creating a Eurasian union met with a restrained 
reaction from leaders of CIS member countries. They described 
it as interesting, but premature. Therefore, one can suppose 
with some confidence that on the shore of Lake Issyk-Kul the 
presidents of Kirghizia, Uzbekistan, and Kazakhstan jointly 
launched an "integration offensive" within the framework of 
bringing regional interests closer together. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60963 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov085cc_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Meet in Kyrgyzstan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Meet in Kyrgyzstan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004165094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1529 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3004165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Presidents of Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and 
Uzbekistan, Nursultan Nazarbayev, Askar Akayev and Islam 
Karimov, had a meeting in Cholpon-Ata, Kyrgyzstan. 
  During the meeting, held at the proposal of Kyrgyzstan 
President Askar Akayev on Friday [29 April] and Saturday, the 
three leaders spoke about the social and political situation in 
their countries, discussed the current state of affairs in 
Central Asia and the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) in 
general, and dealt with some international problems. 
  The presidents said there was a need for practical 
mechanisms 
to carry out the trilateral treaty to create a single economic 
area, an accord which, they said, is in line with the CIS 
economic union treaty and is an instrument for the 
implementation of the latter document within Central Asia. 
  Nazarbayev, Akayev and Karimov also brought up some regional 
political problems, mainly that of migration and consequent 
coexistence between different ethnic groups in Central Asian 
countries, and discussed the damage done to Kyrgyzstan's economy 
by recent mudslides. 
  The presidents issued a joint communique, in which they 
urged 
stronger friendship and cooperation between their countries in 
all fields. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

