<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIS News Agency Conference Stresses Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CIS News Agency Conference Stresses Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904050494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1725 
GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2904050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Veksler] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Apr -- A conference of heads and 
executive directors of news agencies of CIS member-states, which 
finished today at the ITAR-TASS building, has spoken out for the 
need to make efficient use of the unified information space. 
Attending it were delegations from Armenia, Georgia, 
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, 
Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, and Ukraine, as well as 
representatives from the sovereign states' embassies. 
  In the opinion of ARMENPRESS director Gevorka Oganesyan, 
"the 
main result of the meeting is that we have managed to do some 
constructive work after the collapse of the Soviet Union. I 
recall a similar conference last year, which was quite amorphous 
in content and at which those attending had major differences. 
But now, at the insistence of a majority of the agencies, a 
decision in principle has been made to make really effective use 
of the new unified information space. In connection with this, 
an appropriate memorandum to the chairman of the 
Interparliamentary Assembly was passed." 
  "Our Republic is developing along democratic lines, freedom 
of speech and the press is developing, and naturally we need an 
outlet into the international information space," said Akbar 
Ryskulov, director of the Kyrgyzkabar agency. "We are ready to 
cooperate with any professional news agency that propagandizes 
basic human ideals. Furthermore, the more independent we become, 
the more we regard information integration as important and 
topical for us, and the meeting at ITAR-TASS and the documents 
adopted at it will undoubtedly promote the development of this 
process." 
  Boris Petrov, director of ITAR-TASS in St. Petersburg, said 
he was deeply satisfied with the course and character of the 
meeting and the content of the decisions adopted, particularly 
the proposals to create a permanently functioning council of 
heads of CIS news agencies. In his view, "the general situation 
regarding the creation and building of structures to coordinate 
the activity of the CIS has reached a phase that demands the 
creation of a similar structure in the information field as 
well." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60967 </DOCNO>
