<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Maritime Kray Leader Concerned Over Electricity Rate Hike </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Maritime Kray Leader Concerned Over Electricity Rate Hike </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0205194494 Vladivostok Radio Vladivostok Network in 
Russian 0210 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0205194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vladivostok Radio Vladivostok Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Lunch Hour Break" program] </F>
  [Text] A few days ago the people of Maritime Kray were 
literally shocked by the prices for electricity proposed by the 
central government. As Natalya Vstovskaya, press secretary of 
the kray administration head, reported before the beginning of 
the program, Yevgeniy Nazdratenko took part in a meeting of the 
Federal Assembly while in Moscow and signed the Agreement on 
Civic Accord in Russia. I am prepared to welcome any chance 
aimed at stabilizing our society and establishing peace and 
order, he said over the telephone. However, the governor 
expressed deep concern over the situation in connection with the 
increase in prices on electricity. 
  As you know, according to the 22 April decree, the 
government 
is rescinding preferential rates for Maritime Kray set down in 
decree No. 1001. This document was not coordinated with 
Maritime Kray, and I am categorically opposed to such measures, 
Yevgeniy Nazdratenko declared. The head of the administration 
has departed for Vladivostok to deal with urgent kray issues. 
Immediately on arrival he plans to visit the agricultural fair 
and fish market being held today. 
  As was reported earlier, Yevgeniy Nazdratenko was invited to 
the United States for the presentation of the president's book. 
However, he declined the offer. During an audience with Yeltsin 
in Moscow in connection with the publication of the book, I 
explained the necessity for my return to the kray, and I think I 
was understood, the head of the kray administration said. 

</TEXT>

