<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Almaty Mayor Criticizes Government Over Fuel Shortage </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Almaty Mayor Criticizes Government Over Fuel Shortage </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205114994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1053 
GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Fedor Ignatov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty, 2 May (ITAR-TASS) -- The Almaty city 
committee for emergencies announced an emergency situation in 
the capital of Kazakhstan from today. Due to the sharp 
restriction in the supply of fuels to the Almatynefteprodukt 
association and the Munayavtomatizatsiya joint-stock 
association, the dispatch of fuel to all enterprises and 
organizations, apart from those directly providing the city's 
vital facilities, is to be prohibited until special instruction. 
Tough restrictions on the supply of electricity to consumers 
have been introduced. In certain districts of the city, the 
temperature of hot water has been reduced to 40 degrees Celcius. 
  Speaking on republician television, the city's mayor 
Zamanbek 
Nurkadilov said that neither the prime minister nor his deputy 
wishes to discuss the present situation with him. "If the prime 
minister does not want to meet the city's head," Nurkadilov 
said, "and if other high-ranking officials also ignore the 
city's problems, then the natural question arises: Whyt do we 
need such a government?" 
  The mayor expressed hope that the leadership of those 
regions 
which supply the capital of Kazakhstan with coal, petroleum 
products, and gas will not remain indifferent to the emergency 
situation that has been introduced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

