Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bankers Attempt To Restore Order in Banking System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bankers Attempt To Restore Order in Banking System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205155394 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Kazakh 1400 GMT 
2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Kazakh </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Bank of Kazakhstan held a news 
conference devoted to the financial and credit situation in the 
Republic. National Bank Chairman Daulet Sembayev and his 
deputies answered numerous questions and said that "the banking 
system has not yet been properly formed in our state." Founders 
of commercial banks pursued only one aim--to ensure themselves 
with credits--and did not take into consideration the needs of 
their customers. In addition, they were short of money and 
qualified personnel. The possibilities of such banks were 
reduced to a minimum due to granting unjustified or wrongly 
documented soft loans. A great deal of work is currently being 
done in localities in order to increase the authorized funds of 
loan granting banks and to reduce the interference of local 
administrations in these banks' work. The board of the National 
Bank came to a logically based conclusion: Decisions on 
granting soft loans should be made primarily by the government 
and banks, to this effect, should be given additional money. 
The board of the National Bank will hold news conferences 
regularly. This will enable the population to make an informed 
choice and to participate in various financial events and not to 
fall prey to dubious deals. The number of other transgressions 
will also decrease. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

