<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko on Russia's Interest in C. Asia, Caucasus </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko on Russia's Interest in C. Asia, Caucasus </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305094194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0900 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0305094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by KYRGYZKABAR-TASS correspondent Albert Bogdanov] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 3 May TASS -- "Russia's main interest in 
Central Asia and in Transcaucasia is peace," speaker of the 
upper chamber of the Russian parliament Vladimir Shumeyko told a 
press conference here on Monday [2 May] after the signing of an 
agreement on interparliamentary cooperation between Russia and 
Kyrgyzstan. Russian troops in the Caucasian conflict zone serve 
only as a disengagement buffer between the conflicting sides. 
In Shumeyko's opinion, any "war between two CIS nations is an 
obstacle to the development of the Commonwealth of Independent 
States as a whole." 
  Speaker of the Kyrgyz parliament Medetkan Sherimkulov added: 
"We cannot leave Russia to deal with the Karabakh problem alone. 
We must prevent it from being accused of imperial designs when 
it tries to restore peace in this area by its own means. Of 
course, we are aware of Russia's interest in the republics of 
the former Soviet Union. But today Russia can rely not only on 
its own forces. Its efforts are now correctly assessed in all 
the states of our commonwealth." 
  Asked about the plans for achieving peace, Shumeyko said: 
"The MPS are unanimous that the problem should be solved as a 
single whole." Shumeyko indicated three settlement stages: 
complete end of hostilities, withdrawal of all the troops from 
the conflict zone, and conclusion of a peace treaty. "The status 
of Nagorno-Karabakh can be determined only after that," he 
stated. 
  Shumeiko, together with his counterpart Medetkan 
Sherimkulov, 
flew to the southern part of the republic today to visit 
districts hit by a recent natural calamity. 

</TEXT>

