<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investigation Begun Into Uzbek Plane Seizure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investigation Begun Into Uzbek Plane Seizure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205140994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1009 
GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vitaliy Gordiyenko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 May (ITAR-TASS) -- A special commission 
has started an investigation into yesterday's incident at 
airport at Khorog (the administrative center of Gorno-Badakhshan 
autonomous oblast), in which armed opposition fighters seized a 
military aircraft from Uzbekistan. The ITAR-TASS correspondent 
was told today over the telephone by informed sources in 
Tajikistan's Government circles that because of conflicting 
reports from Khorog it is impossible to confirm or refute the 
definition of the incident as a "seizure" of the cargo delivered 
by the AN-26 aircraft from Uzbekistan to Khorog pending 
completion of the commission's work. 
  Meanwhile, as was reported earlier, Uzbekistan's Defense 
Ministry confirmed yesterday that the cargo described as 
"humanitarian aid" had indeed been prepared for delivery to 
Gorno-Badakhshan. But for unknown reasons the relevant bodies 
in Tajikistan were not informed beforehand about the time when 
the state border would be crossed. The aircraft landed at 1500 
local time at the Khorog airport. After the landing the runway 
and the approaches to the airport were cordoned off by fighters 
from a detachment of "Tajik Self-Defense Forces." The cargo on 
board was taken away. In view of this, military sources in 
Dushanbe do not rule out the possibility that contacts have been 
established between certain forces in Uzbekistan and fighters in 
the Pamir mountains, and that these contacts have some bearing 
on the situation in the region. 

</TEXT>

