<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission Claims Plane Not Seized by Opposition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission Claims Plane Not Seized by Opposition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205145294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1340 
GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vitaliy Gordenko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 May (ITAR-TASS) -- According to the 
preliminary results produced by the commission investigating 
yesterday's report about the Uzbek plane in Khorog airport, it 
was not seized by armed Tajik opposition forces. An ITAR-TASS 
correspondent was told over the phone today by sources in well- 
informed government circles in the Republic that the special 
commission has established that the plane was on a scheduled 
flight for the joint peace-keeping forces and was carrying 
humanitarian aid. 
  The same source said the commission established that, 
contrary to the reports coming in, the plane was not seized and 
there were no armed people from the Tajik opposition at the 
airport. The same source said that, because of Khorog's 
location and the situation in the region, all planes coming into 
the airport are regarded from the standpoint of security. As 
for the AN-26 plane which was apparently seized, it left Khorog 
at 1627 and no problems were registered. Two other planes in 
addition to the AN-26 landed at Khorog airport from Dushanbe on 
that day. 
  Tajik Foreign Minister Rashid Olimov told an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent in a telephone interview that an official 
statement would be made tomorrow about the results of the 
investigation into this episode. 

</TEXT>

