<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Foreign Minister `Most Popular Politician' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Foreign Minister `Most Popular Politician' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205150994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1318 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0205150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to a poll, Armenia's ex-Foreign Minister 
Raffi Ovannisyan is the most popular politician in that republic 
in April. 
  He was favoured by 73.2 percent of the 1200 Armenians, 
polled 
by the Center for Sociological Studies at the Republican Academy 
of Sciences. 
  President Levon Ter-Petrosyan proved popular with only 22.9 
percent of the interviewed, 57.1 percent voiced dislike for him. 
  Nor does the Prime Minister Hrant Bagratyan enjoy 
popularity. 
He was spoken of favorably only 11.6 percent of the 
respondents, 73.2 percent said he was no good. 
  The most popular party, according to the poll, is 
Dashnaktsutyun, an opposition revolutionary federation. Going 
next is the Armenian Communist Party. The ruling Armenian 
National Movement comes only third in the list. 
  Of foreign politicians, the U.S. President Bill Clinton and 
Russia's President Boris Yeltsin enjoy the greatest popularity 
in Armenia. 

</TEXT>

