<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nagorno-Karabakh `Pins Certain Hopes' on CIS Assembly </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nagorno-Karabakh `Pins Certain Hopes' on CIS Assembly </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205151394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1318 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0205151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nagorno-Karabakh "pins certain hopes" on the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly, which has stepped up its peace 
mission in an attempt to settle the Karabakh conflict. This has 
been declared in an interview with journalists in Stepanakert by 
Karen Baburyan, the acting chairman of the parliament of the 
self-proclaimed Nagorno-Karabakh Republic. 
  He leads a Karabakh delegation to Kyrgyzstan's capital 
Bishkek to take part in a meeting of the heads of Armenian and 
Azerbaijani parliaments. Mediated by the CIS Interparliamentary 
Assembly, the meeting has been scheduled for 3-6 May. 
  In Baburyan's words, the gathering in Bishkek will largely 
depend on the position of Azerbaijan, "whose leadership is not 
too willing to maintain contact with Karabakh." He noted that 
broader contacts "would help to lead the conflict out of the 
deadlock." 
  Taking part in the Bishkek meeting, initiated by the Kyrgyz 
Parliament's Chairman Meditkan Sherimkulov and the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly, will be the Assembly's Chairman 
Vladimir Shumeyko, the head of Russia's Federation Council. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

