<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Sees New Stage in Building Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Sees New Stage in Building Armed Forces </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205145994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1318 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0205145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze has declared 
that last week's appointment of the Lieutenant-General Varden 
Nadibaidze, the former deputy commander of a group of Russian 
troops in Transcaucasia, to the post of republican defence 
minister, starts a new stage in building up the Georgian armed 
forces. "New professional approaches are essential. That's 
precisely what guided me in nominating Nadibaidze to the 
office," Shevardnadze remarked and described the new minister as 
"an experienced specialist, a good organizer, versed in army 
matters and weaponry." 
  He emphasized that "without cooperation and friendship with 
Russia at this stage it is impossible to man a truly national 
Georgian Army to guarantee the country's independence." This, 
in his words, is clear from the experience of the last few years. 
  Turning to a scandal in Georgian parliament on 28 April, 
when 
the Vice-Speaker Vakhtang Rcheulishvili splashed water out of a 
glass into the face of the Popular Front's leader Nodar Natadze, 
Shevardnadze declared that there are forces in parliament today, 
wishing to rekindle instability in the country. He dismissed 
these attempts as unnecessary and unfeasible. 
  In conclusion, he called Georgian citizens for unity and 
concord. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

