<H3> <TI>   President: Summit May Break `Deadlock' in Russian Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President: Summit May Break `Deadlock' in Russian Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205115694 Tallinn ETA in English 0810 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From 30 April EESTI SENUMID, HOMMIKULEHT, POSTIMEES, p 1, </F>
4; "News Bulletin" No. 83/94] 
  [Excerpt] Monday, 2 May -- A summit meeting might help to 
end the deadlock in Estonian-Russian relations, President 
Lennart Meri told at a meeting with a group of Russian 
journalists on Thursday [28 April]. 
  Delayed negotiations have a negative feature of making the 
delegations concentrate on details and forcing them to forget 
the strategic directions, Meri said. He hoped that a meeting 
with the Russian president might give new life to the 
negotiations. The president admitted that his contacts with 
Boris Yeltsin have been limited to letters so far. "Obviously, 
the relations with the Baltic states are not a central issue of 
the Russian foreign policy and the negotiations have been slowed 
down accordingly," he said. 
  Meri welcomed the idea of finding an international mediator, 
for example, the president of Finland. He also said that the 
freezing of the Estonian-Russian border issue for 5-10 years 
could be possible in order to enable to find a correct solution 
to the issue. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

