<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Notes Trade Status With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Notes Trade Status With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205144894 Tallinn BNS in English 1350 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Riga, May 02, BNS -- Latvian and Russian state 
delegations signed a protocol on the most favored nation status 
in economy, Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs told reporters 
Sunday [1 May] on return from Moscow. 
  Under the protocol, the favored nation relations take effect 
starting 1 June. The respective agreement is scheduled for the 
second half of May when Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin tours Riga. 
  Birkavs draw a link between the achieved compromise on the 
amount of rent for the Skrunda radar and the agreement on the 
most favored nation status in economy. 
  As reported, Russia initially offered Latvia 2 million U.S. 
dollars per year while Latvia demanded 400 million U.S. dollars 
per year. 
  The 30 April troop withdrawal treaty provides for a 
$5-million yearly rent. Birkavs pledged to channel the funding 
for the needs of Skrunda locals who will have to put up with the 
radar for four more years. 
  Latvia needs long-term goodneighborly relations with Russia, 
said Birkavs. He claimed that Latvia and Russia faced a new 
historic epoch in this aspect. 
  "The new, democratic Russia understands Latvia's problems 
and 
the signature of the agreements will consolidate democracy also 
in Russia itself," noted Birkavs. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

