<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Welcome of Russian Withdrawal Pact Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Welcome of Russian Withdrawal Pact Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205144694 Tallinn BNS in English 1350 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, 2 May, BNS -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on 
Saturday [30 April] welcomed the signing of an agreement on 
Russian troop withdrawal from Latvia. 
  The withdrawal package was signed by Presidents Guntis 
Ulmanis of Latvia and Boris Yeltsin of Russia in Moscow on 
Saturday. 
  Clinton in his foreign policy radio address the same day 
called the Latvian-Russian agreement historic, adding that 
"these and other promising developments were made possible, in 
part, by American support and resolve." 
  The United States had an important role in helping to 
overcome a deadlock during the talks on the issue of the Russian 
early-warning radar station at Skrunda, Latvia. 
  The U.S. President at his visit to Moscow in January 
received 
Russia's proposal, according to which the facility remains under 
Russian control for the next four years, plus for a 1.5-year 
term necessary for its dismantling. 
  This proposal, later accepted by Latvia, was turned over in 
Washington to Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis during his late 
January-early February visit. 

</TEXT>

