<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister, President Discuss Yeltsin Letter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister, President Discuss Yeltsin Letter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205144494 Tallinn BNS in English 1350 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, 2 May, BNS -- A high-ranking Russian 
Foreign Ministry official should come to Lithuania to discuss 
relations between the two countries, Lithuanian Foreign Minister 
Povilas Gylys said Monday [2 May] after his meeting with 
President Algirdas Brazauskas. 
  Gylys told reporters that he and Brazauskas spoke about the 
exchange of letters between Lithuanian and Russian presidents, 
as well as the problems discussed in them. "There are things to 
negotiate about," Gylys said, but noted that preparations for 
further talks only started. 
  Brazauskas last Friday received Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin's letter implying that the implementation of bilateral 
economic treaties is bound up with the problem of Russian 
transit to the Kaliningrad region through Lithuanian territory. 
  Minister Gylys emphasized that Russian transit through 
Lithuania is currently carried out according to Lithuanian 
rules. The minister said he intends to discuss the strategy of 
transit talks with the head of the working group for talks with 
the CIS, Virgilijus Bulovas. 
  Gylys said he and Brazauskas also discussed the results of 
the minister's recent visits to the United States and several 
Latin American countries. The minister said they analyzed 
proposals for political, economic, diplomatic and cultural 
cooperation brought from Venezuela, Brazil, Uruguay, and 
Argentina. 

</TEXT>

