<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Chair Praises Latvian Accord, RSA Vote </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Chair Praises Latvian Accord, RSA Vote </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0205145194 Tallinn BNS in English 1350 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0205145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, 2 May, BNS -- Lithuanian Parliament 
Chairman Ceslovas Jursenas says he is pleased with the 
agreements signed between Latvia and Russia to withdraw Russian 
troops from Latvian territory by 31 Aug. 
  At a press conference in Vilnius Monday [2 May], Jursenas 
said he is glad that "one more Baltic state will be free of a 
foreign army." 
  The parliament chairman noted, however, that the agreements 
signed last Saturday in Moscow are not as good as "wanted by 
Latvia and us." Jursenas said his reservation primarily concerns 
a permission for Russia to keep its radar base in Skrunda for 
another several years, although "forward movement is impossible 
without compromises." 
  Jursenas criticized Vytautas Landsbergis, leader of the 
rightist opposition in the Lithuanian parliament, for calling 
Latvia the weakest Baltic link that was broken by Russia. The 
parliament chairman said it is unethical to "criticize a sister 
of one fate in such a way and to call her names." 
  Jursenas also praised the first all-race election in the 
"far-away" South Africa. He said the election buried the 
apartheid system, which has completely discredited itself in the 
course of years. The South African election was observed by 
Lithuanian Parliament Vice Chairman Aloyzas Sakalas. 

</TEXT>

