<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Landsbergis Warns on Concessions to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Landsbergis Warns on Concessions to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205160194 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1400 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205160194 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vytautas Landsbergis, leader of the Seimas 
right-wing opposition, has warned that no concessions should be 
made to Russia because this would mean that Russia's method of 
arm-twisting has been recognized, and new pressures would follow. 
  This is how Vytautas Landsbergis commented on the news that 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin admitted in his letter to 
Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas that Russia linked the 
implementation of economic agreements signed last autumn with 
transit from the Karaliaucius [Kaliningrad] region. 
  Having received this letter, President Algirdas Brazauskas 
told journalists that Lithuania cannot agree to Russia's policy 
in this respect. According to him, the agreement signed in 
Vilnius last November was the result of one stage of 
negotiations, however, negotiations concerning the transit from 
the Kaliningrad region and the visa regime is a matter of 
further negotiations. 
  Vytautas Landsbergis said that he believes that President 
Algirdas Brazauskas is not inclined to give in, however, 
contracts and prices for transit fixed by lower-ranking 
officials remain in the realm of unanswered questions. If the 
income for the state budget is rejected by one's own will, then 
this looks like corruption, Vytautas Landsbergis said [sentence 
as heard]. This was a Baltic News Service report. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

