<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reasons for Not Signing Social Treaty Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reasons for Not Signing Social Treaty Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0205110594 Moscow PRAVDA in Russian 30 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0205110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Valentina Nikiforova report: "Nonsignatories"] </F>
  [Text] Here is the official report -- of the 248 
participants in the assembly, 245 signed the "Social Accord 
Treaty." Those are impressive figures. It was not signed by G. 
Zyuganov, chairman of the Russian Federation Communist Party 
Central Executive Committee, or by N. Vinogradov and A. Tuleyev, 
chairmen of the oblast legislative assemblies of Vladimir and 
Kemerovo Oblasts respectively. 
  That would seem to be minor opposition. But that depends. 
If the leader of one of the largest political parties, which 
won one-third of the seats in the Federal Assembly elections, 
does not sign, then the organizers of the second edition of the 
failed "political new year" should ponder on it. It is not as a 
result of trivial disagreements that the Communist leader is 
refusing to sign -- the party disagrees with the policy of the 
president and the government and is calling for it to be 
changed. For the sake of peace, harmony, and a dignified life. 
  The Yavlinskiy-Boldyrev-Lukin deputies' faction was among 
the 
refuseniks. Its leader rightly believes that agreement can only 
be achieved on a specific issue. 
  The Agrarian Party of Russia had reasonable objections. The 
court chroniclers have called them self-seeking. Perhaps 
because the agrarians are sounding the alarm? Spring is in full 
swing, and there are major difficulties with the sowing -- what 
will be left in the silos this fall?... 
  So those who are not signing the red papers are people whose 
view of Russia is not conditioned by the Kremlin. 

</TEXT>

