<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Greets Journalists on Press Freedom Day </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Greets Journalists on Press Freedom Day </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305095294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0924 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0305095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 3 TASS -- "Every Russian citizen must 
always be sure that he will get only trustworthy information, 
only the truth from our newspapers, magazines, television and 
radio," Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin says in his message 
of greetings to Russian journalists on the occasion of the world 
freedom of the press day and the opening of the spring holidays 
of the free press. 
  "On the day of your professional holiday I want to wish you 
all from the bottom of my heart the best of health, creactive 
achievements, and successes in your far from easy job," the 
document says. "I respect your work very much, because it 
requires not only skill, but courage, civic audacity, and a huge 
sense of responsibility for the future and honour of our great 
Russia." 
  Chernomyrdin stresses that the freedom of the press, which 
is 
now the common boon of all the Russian people, is a great social 
achievement of the reviving Russia, which gives the journalists 
access to any information. "The government," the premier said, 
"is doing everything it can to allow every journalist, every 
citizen, to exercise his right to obtain information. It will 
back the mass media as much as it can, will make a practical 
contribution to the successful work of newspaper workers, 
publishers, TV and radio journalists." 

</TEXT>

