<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   March Figures Show Recession Continuing To Worsen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    March Figures Show Recession Continuing To Worsen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0205150794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 30 Apr 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0205150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [BIZNES-TASS report: "The Lower the Inflation, the Worse </F>
the Recession"] 
  [Text] The first quarter of 1994 saw the greatest 
reduction in industrial production since the reforms began. 
Whereas in February there had been some slowing down in the 
pace of the recession, in March the decline in production 
accelerated again. This information comes from the Russian 
Federation Ministry of the Economy. 
  In the first quarter of 1994 the depth of the recession in 
industrial production was over 20 percent compared with the 
corresponding period last year. Whereas at the beginning of 
last year the dynamics of the recession were beginning to ease 
off, this year the movement is heading upward (January -- 23.1 
percent, February -- 24.1 percent, March -- 27.4 percent). 
  In the opinion of Economy Ministry experts, the greatest 
reduction has occurred in the processing sectors. At 26.8 
percent the fall in the production of consumer goods was greater 
than the fall in industry as a whole. 
  As the chief of a ministry department said in conversation 
with your BIZNES-TASS correspondent, the greatest cause for 
concern today is the fact that the reforms have not touched the 
technological structure of production. The majority of 
enterprises cannot reduce production costs and thus cannot cope 
with the reduced demand, especially at a time of substantially 
increased competition in the domestic market from foreign 
producers. 

</TEXT>

