<F P=101> Economic &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Latest Central Bank Credit Auction Fails </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Latest Central Bank Credit Auction Fails </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0205172994 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 30 Apr 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0205172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Kucherenko report: "Third Credit Auction Did Not </F>
Go Ahead"] 
  [Text] The third credit auction to place Bank of Russia 
centralized loans with Moscow banks was to have been held in 
Moscow 26 April, but like the second one it did not go ahead. 
  According to the Central Bank of Russia's Moscow 
administration, a total of 9 billion rubles was put up for 
auction at an annual interest rate of 203 percent, that is 5 
percent below the Central Bank rate. However, none of the 
Moscow banks applied to take part in the auction. 
  It is thought that the reason for this is the extremely 
tough 
requirements that auction participants have to meet, and 
therefore people wanting to buy money were simply afraid of 
showing "Central Bank operatives" the state of their affairs. 
At the same time "robust" Moscow establishments which could 
quite easily have gained access to the auction already have 
adequate resources. There is no reason for them to acquire 
credit: An interbank market developed in Moscow long ago, where 
money can be bought far more cheaply. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

