<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on Vympel Missile Design Bureau </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Report on Vympel Missile Design Bureau </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205134294 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1100 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by Aleksandr Onosovskiy; from the "Novosti" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] The Vympel design bureau is one of the oldest 
research centers of the Russian defense industry. It designs 
missiles of all ranges for combat aircraft. In this type of 
armament Russia still maintains its superiority -- to a large 
extent thanks to Vympel. For example, not even the U.S. Army has 
a reverse start missile like our R-73E [AA-11 `Archer' class], 
which is designed for close-range dogfights. The air-to-air 
AAM-AE missile [AA-X-12] is equal in quality to its U.S. 
counterpart, [AIM-120 A] AMRAAM, while costing only half as 
much. There are missiles capable of hitting targets at a range 
of hundreds of miles. The list can go on and on. 
  But like most defense industry enterprises, Vympel finds it 
hard to work now. Because of a shortage of funds, it is 
continually forced to reduce long-term research, which gives an 
impetus to the creation of new types of armament. Yet the 
acclaimed design bureau still manages to maintain its 
reputation. The newest missile system was tested recently on 
the MiG-31M [`Foxhound-B'] aircraft. The Russian president 
himself congratulated the work force on the success of the 
experiment. Now Vympel cherishes justifiable hopes for serious 
support. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

