<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Emphasizes Peaceful Methods in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Emphasizes Peaceful Methods in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0205122594 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 30 Apr 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PM0205122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Correspondent Igor Yavlinskiy report under "INFORM" rubric: </F>
"Andrey Vladimirovich, Are You Pro-Serb?"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- Andrey Kozyrev and his German colleague 
Klaus Kinkel know each other well and can get down to business 
without any preliminaries. That is why Kozyrev managed to pack 
a lot into the three hours he was on German soil. He and his 
team traveled by military helicopter to Bonn's "Petersberg" 
residence for honored guests, he had a conversation with Kinkel, 
he had a bite to eat, and he appeared before journalists. 
  The agenda included: putting the final touches to the 
program for Boris Yeltsin's upcoming visit to the FRG; an 
exchange of opinions on the progress of the elections in the 
Republic of South Africa; discussion of the situation in the 
Near East; and problems of bilateral relations. But the key 
question was Bosnia and, in particular, President Yeltsin's 
proposal to hold an international meeting on settling the 
conflict with Russia, the United States, the EU [European 
Union], and NATO participating. In the minister's opinion, it 
should specifically result in a consolidated approach to this 
problem from the world community. Russian diplomacy's main 
thesis is that there must be no reliance purely on a military 
solution involving force and that it is essential to try to make 
full use of all peaceful methods to extinguish the conflagration 
of war in the Balkans. A meeting of foreign ministers of the 
states and political organizations invited by Boris Nikolayevich 
to the conversation on Bosnia is due to be held in the near 
future in order to reach final agreement on disputed points. 
  The world community's next task is to insist on a cease-fire 
in Bosnia and to start working out the conditions for and 
principles of a comprehensive peace settlement. And, as 
progress is made toward the set aim, the vise of economic 
sanctions against Yugoslavia must be gradually loosened. 
  "Do you represent the Serbs' interests?" a German journalist 
asked. 
  "No, I represent Russia," Andrey Vladimirovich replied. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61051 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov085_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Outlines Stances on Mideast Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Outlines Stances on Mideast Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305123494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1106 
GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Denis Perkin] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 3 May -- The forthcoming signing of the 
"Gaza-Jericho-First" agreement between the PLO and Israel will 
open a new, no less complex stage connected with the 
implementation of the agreements which have been reached, 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev stated today before his 
departure for Cairo where he is to take part in the ceremony at 
which that historic document will be signed. [passage omitted] 
  In the opinion of the Russian minister, questions on the 
practical transition to a peaceful life, on setting up economic 
ties, and guaranteeing security are of exceptional importance 
for the whole region. It is gratifying that Russia also has 
made its contribution to the achievement of progress along this 
path. In particular, "it is generally acknowledged" that the 
recent visits to Moscow by the PLO and Israeli delegations, the 
meetings which Yasir 'Arafat and Yitzhaq Rabin had with Boris 
Yeltsin "gave a good boost to the work being carried out," 
A.Kozyrev noted. 
  He also voiced satisfaction with the constructive 
cooperation 
which is under way with the U.S. side. "We are are in daily 
contact, we are acting in unison, in complete accord," the 
minister stressed. 
  A. Kozyrev expressed confidence that the present first step 
in the Near East peace process should be accompanied by the 
search for mutually acceptable solutions with regard to all 
Palestinian territories and by progress in other areas of the 
talks. The minister believes that it is necessary, first and 
foremost, to attain progress in the Israel-Syrian area of the 
talks, as the most difficult one. In his words, Russia has an 
opportunity to play an active mediatory role. 
  Touching upon Russia's idea of convening the second Madrid 
conference on the Near East, A. Kozyrev noted that it aimed to 
open new "political-diplomatic" prospects and that it is still 
topical, of course. "I think," he continued, "that this idea 
will receive a wider recognition since a certain stage in the 
current process is now coming to completion." It is necessary 
to assess the path which has been traveled and to specifically 
outline future areas of the talks to capitalize on the 
achievements of the first Madrid conference. 
  In the opinion of the Russian minister, the present peace 
process could become a model for resolving many "chronic 
conflicts fraught with bloodshed and intolerance." This applies 
in particular, he noted, to the Karabakh conflict. A.Kozyrev 
voiced the hope that the warring sides will be able to reach 
agreement on a cease-fire and to "enter an agreement drawn up 
with Russian mediation." 
  The head of the foreign policy department of the Russian 
Federation noted that the Interparliamentary Assembly of CIS 
states could make a weighty contribution to resolving this 
problem. "We will also strive to step up cooperation in this 
direction in the CSCE," he said. 
  The minister also said that he intended to meet soon with 
Jan 
Eliasson, chairman of the CSCE peace conference on 
Nagorno-Karabakh. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

