<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Against Using Pressure on Iraq </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Against Using Pressure on Iraq </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004162194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1327 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3004162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian foreign policy-makers are attentively 
observing the situation in the Persian Gulf. Moscow wants to 
contribute to a settlement of the conflict there as well as in 
any other region of the world and seeks stability and friendly 
relations established in the region. Moscow considers this to 
be in its direct state interests, a Russian expert on this 
region's problems told INTERFAX in an interview. 
  He suggested that the Russian position on elimination of the 
consequences of the Iraqi-Kuwait conflict proceeded from the 
priority of international law. "This means that Baghdad must 
strictly observe and implement all the decisions made by the 
world community. The UN Security Council in its turn must 
adequately response to all positive moves by Iraq," he added. 
  The expert pointed out that three years after the armed 
conflict Iraq had done much for implementation of the decisions 
made by the UN Security Council, primarily in the sphere of 
disarmament. 
  The expert said this had caused the Russian representative 
to 
the UN Security Council to propose at its last session that the 
"work" with Iraq proceed to the next stage providing for 
international control over the Iraqi military programs. 
  "Moscow, Paris, Beijing and several nonpermanent members of 
the UN Security Council believe that such specific measures 
would encourage Baghdad for further cooperation with the Special 
Commission," the expert suggested. 
  He said Moscow was afraid that a continuing indefinite 
position on lifting the sanctions and utilization of pressure 
and threats in dialogue with Iraq might bring results opposite 
to expectations, such as confrontation with the UN and a closed 
defense policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

