<H3> <TI>   Aide Outlines Chernomyrdin's Planned Foreign Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aide Outlines Chernomyrdin's Planned Foreign Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305110694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1044 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0305110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [(Text] An advisor of the Russian prime-minister Mikhail 
Tarasov has told INTERFAX that this year Viktor Chernomyrdin is 
to intensively travel abroad. Still visits to Russian regions 
and republics to see the situation and problems remain his 
priority. 
  Tarasov said that in mid-May the head of the cabinet is 
expected to make a one-day visit to Warsaw to resolve old 
problems blocking bilateral economic cooperation, in particular 
mutual settlements and the foreign debt of the former Soviet 
Union. 
  A visit to China is planned for the end of May. There 
Chernomyrdin should sign an impressive package of agreements, 
including documents on the demarcation of the border, shipping 
on the Amur river and in international waters, cooperation in 
agriculture and related industries as well as in environmental 
protection. 
  In June the prime-minister is expected to take part in the 
third session of the Gore-Chernomyrdin commission in the USA. 
In the framework of the commission six mixed committees have 
planned joint energy, space and nuclear power engineering 
projects. 
  In the second half of July, according to Tarasov, the 
Russian 
head of government is expected to tour Saudi Arabia, the United 
Arab Emirates and Kuwait. There attention will be centered 
around military-technical cooperation, the attraction of foreign 
investments and cooperation in fuel and power engineering. 
  The Russian Prime-Minister has been invited to visit the 
Czech republic and Slovakia as well as Bulgaria and Rumania. 
  At the end of the year he is expected to go to London. 
  During the next few months in Moscow Chernomyrdin is to hold 
talks with his counterparts from Austria, Vietnam, Mongolia, 
Denmark and other foreign countries. 

</TEXT>

