<H3> <TI>   Navy Denies Reports on Pacific Fleet Maneuvers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Navy Denies Reports on Pacific Fleet Maneuvers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205133994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1254 
GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 May (ITAR-TASS) -- The Russian Pacific 
Fleet is not conducting maneuvers and is not taking part in any 
exercises. This was how the Russian Navy's press center 
commented on reports by the foreign mass media about Pacific 
Fleet vessels taking part "in wide-scale maneuvers in the region 
of the South Kurils." It is alleged that Russia's surface 
fleet, in conjunction with ground and border troops, is working 
on the task of seizing foreign territories there. 
  It was explained to the ITAR-TASS correspondent at the 
Navy's 
main headquarters that the Red Banner Pacific Fleet is at 
present engaged in its usual training according to the schedule 
approved by the Russian Federation Defense Ministry. Seven of 
the fleet's warships are being used in the "Putina" operation 
aimed at protecting the nation's natural wealth, including in 
the region of the South Kurils. The fleet's participation in 
joint actions with border guards and the air force to protect 
the state border and to curb mass poaching which is detrimental 
to Russia has not been concealed. It was specifically reported 
in both the Russian and foreign mass media. 
  In the view of specialists of the Navy's main headquarters, 
the situation in the Far East is rather difficult. However, in 
their words, it is not a case of our fleet being "aggressive," 
but rather of the rapidly changing situation. Pacific Fleet 
warships and forces of the Russian Border Troops are stepping up 
their efforts [to increase] the effectiveness of the "Putina" 
operation. This is not to the liking of those who in recent 
years have grown accustomed to making brazen use of marine 
resources which by rights belong exclusively to Russia. Naval 
seamen claim that this explains the appearance of material 
misinforming the world public. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

