<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Accepts Invitation to Naples G-7 Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Accepts Invitation to Naples G-7 Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205162594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1532 
GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Startsev] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 2 May -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has 
accepted with satisfaction the invitation to attend the G-7 
meeting to take place in Naples this July. As became known 
today from informed sources within the office of the chairman of 
the Italian Council of Ministers, the Russian president had sent 
a message to Carlo Azeglio Ciampi in which he noted the head of 
the Italian Government's great contribution to attaining 
agreement on Russian participation in examining political issues 
of international security and in preparing the meeting's final 
political document. This decision, the message notes, creates 
good prerequisites for the Naples meeting to become an important 
new milestone in relations between Russia and the G-7. 
  As is known, in late April, C.A. Ciampi told B. Yeltsin 
about 
a preliminary timetable and the form of Russian participation in 
the forthcoming summit. The head of government of Italy, the 
country that currently holds the G-7 presidency, made 
considerable efforts to ensure that the Naples summit be held as 
"seven plus one." It is noteworthy that Russia will not only 
take part in discussing political problems, but will also be 
directly involved in preparations for the Naples conference. B. 
Yeltsin's letter says that he has instructed the Russian 
Federation Government to join most actively in preparations for 
the summit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

