<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK President To Visit Moscow, Uzbekistan in June </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK President To Visit Moscow, Uzbekistan in June </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405051094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0420 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0405051094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Zakharchenko] </F>
  [Text] Seoul May 4 -- South Korean President Kim Yong-sam 
will come to the Russian Federation on a four-day official visit 
between June 1 and 4 at the invitation of President Boris 
Yeltsin as well as to Uzbekistan on a three-day visit at the 
invitation of President Islam Karimov, the spokesman of the 
president's office said at a briefing in Seoul on Wednesday. 
  According to the spokesman, the South Korean president will 
visit the Russian port city of Vladivostok on his way back home. 
  Kim plans to hold talks with Yeltsin during the visit, at 
which the sides will exchange opinions on the situation on the 
Korean peninsula and the situation in the world as a whole. 
They will also discuss ways of strengthening bilateral 
relations. 
  "The visit by President Kim Yong-sam to Russia will help to 
strengthen further relations between the two countries for the 
sake of preserving peace on the Korean peninsula and will step 
up bilateral cooperation in joint development of natural 
resources and technological development for the sake of mutual 
prosperity of the two countries," stressed the spokesman. 
  He added that "the coming visit will have great importance 
for building the foundations of foreign policy by which the 
Korean civil government abides, focusing on the development of 
relations with the four neighbouring powers". 
  In accordance with this diplomacy, Kim visited the United 
States last November as well as Japan and China last March. He 
will go to Russia this time. 
  In June 1989, Kim was in Moscow as the leader of the 
opposition Democratic Party for Reunification. He met Yeltsin 
in Seoul in the capacity of a candidate for the highest state 
post from the ruling Democratic Liberal Party during the Russian 
president's visit to South Korea in November 1992. 
  Presidents Kim and Karimov will discuss chances for 
developing relations between the two countries. Incidentally, 
the largest community of Koreans in the countries of the 
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) lives in Uzbekistan. 
  The South Korean-Uzbek summit "will help to establish 
relations in the economic and other spheres also with other CIS 
members which recently gained independence", the spokesman noted. 

</TEXT>

