<H3> <TI>   EU Spokesman Notes `Remarkable Progress' in Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Spokesman Notes `Remarkable Progress' in Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305195094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1858 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0305195094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Mineyev] </F>
  [Text] Brussels May 3 TASS -- Press secretary of deputy 
head of the commission of the European Union Leon Brittan 
described Brittan's Moscow negotiations as remarkable progress. 
  He told a briefing at the commission today the negotiations 
with Russian Vice-Premier Aleksandr Shokhin aimed to sign the 
long-awaited agreement on partnership and cooperation between 
the European Union and Russia. 
  Although the sides have not finalized all the problems, the 
commission is optimistic about the agreement conclusion and 
contacts with the Russian vice-premier will be continued on 
telefax and over the telephone. 
  In the words of the press secretary, the sides reached good 
progress in the sphere of nuclear material trade, which is the 
main of the three problems in the agreement. The rest two -- on 
sea transport and activities of European banks in Russia -- will 
be settled as soon as the first problem is eliminated, he noted. 
  It is the matter of a compromise between some members of the 
European Union, including France, which fear the inflow into the 
European market of a large amount of cheap nuclear materials, 
and Russia, who wants to include nuclear material trade in the 
agreement alongside the trade of other goods, that is without 
discrimination. The Russian proposal to specify this problem 
with letters is being discussed. 
  After specific aspects of the draft document are finalized 
with Russia, the commission will pass it over to governments of 
the European Union member-states for consultations. 

</TEXT>

