<H3> <TI>   Diplomatic Relations Formalized With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomatic Relations Formalized With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0405004994 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 26 Apr 94 p 1A </F>
<F P=103> PA0405004994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Quintero de Leon] </F>
  [Text] After six years of negotiations that began with the 
military government of Panama, the Republic of Panama yesterday 
formally established diplomatic relations with the Russian 
Federation in a ceremony attended by Panamanian Foreign Minister 
Jose Raul Mulino and his Russian counterpart, Andrey Kozyrev, in 
Moscow. 
  The Panamanian Foreign Ministry disclosed that the two 
ministers signed an agreement called the "Declaration of 
Principles of Relations and Cooperation Between the Russian 
Federation and the Republic of Panama." The essence of the 
agreement is the expansion of the respective countries' consular 
missions to the level of embassies. 
  Consular relations began in 1991 when President Guillermo 
Endara and President Boris Yeltsin decided to establish 
consulates to handle trade relations and cooperation between the 
two countries. 
  A Foreign Ministry bulletin reports Foreign Minister Kozyrev 
said that the Russian Federation considers Panama a future 
economic and financial power, and that he wants to strengthen 
trade relations. 
  In addition, Minister Mulino offered Panama's cooperation on 
banking issues, the Free Trade Zone, the reinsurance system, and 
on "maintaining constant consultation on Latin American 
geopolitical issues." 

</TEXT>

