<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 4 May TASS -- Working groups of the 
Commonwealth Inter-Parliamentary Assembly met in the capital of 
Kyrgyzia [Kyrgyzstan] today to discuss the Nagorno-Karabakh 
problems and look for ways of settling the crisis. 
  The meeting was opened by President Askar Akayev of 
Kyrgyzia. 
In his opening address the president expressed the desire to 
see the meeting make "the first step towards the peaceful 
settlement of the Karabakh conflict." 
  Taking part in the forum are Chairman of the Board of the 
Inter- Parliamentary Assembly Vladimir Shumeyko, Speaker of the 
Parliament of Kyrgyzstan [as received] Afiyaddin Dzhalilov, 
Armenian Parliament Chairman Babken Araktsyan, representatives 
of Nagorno-Karabakh lead by Karen Baburyan. Roger Janson of 
Finland is attending as an observer. 
  On the eve of the meeting Vladimir Shumeyko told journalists 
that he was attaching great significance to negotiations on the 
Karabakh problem. It is impermissible for two countries both of 
which are members of the Commonwealth to wage war against each 
other, he said. Recently Azerbaijan agreed to recognise 
Nagorno-Karabakh as a party to the conflict, which marked a 
considerable shift, which increases chances of success. 
  Afiyaddin Dzhalilov said before leaving Baku for Bishkek 
that 
the Azeri side regards the meeting in the Kyrgyz capital as an 
important step along the path of settling the conflict. 
  Along with this he declared that the Commonwealth 
member-states "must at last recognise that Armenia's actions are 
aggressive and express due political evaluation thereof." 

</TEXT>

